properties.location: Loddon River Laanecoorie to Loddon Weir
properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Loddon River Laanecoorie to Loddon Weir.

Moderate flooding may occur along the Loddon River Laanecoorie to Loddon Weir. 
  • The Loddon River D/S Laanecoorie is currently at 2.97 metres and rising, just below the moderate flood level. 
  • The Loddon River D/S Laanecoorie may remain around the moderate flood level (3.00 m) during Saturday.
The latest community newsletter from Saturday 29 October is available here: Community Newsletter
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater. You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. 
  • Check the VicRoads website traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au for information on road closures.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
Mosquito Alert    
With the recent floods in many areas across Victoria, the risk of mosquito breeding is high. Learn more about how to protect yourself and your family at https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/protect-yourself-mosquito-borne-disease

What you can do:
  • Cover up - wear long, loose-fitting clothing.  
  • Use repellents that contain picaridin. 
  • Use mosquito nets or insect screens. 
  • Limit activity outdoors and move indoors if possible. 
Flood Recovery Hotline - Call 1800 560 760
Flood Recovery Hotline is a single state-wide number, 1800 560 760, that Victorians impacted by the October 2022 floods can call for help or assistance with:
  • navigating available supports
  • clean-up
  • temporary accommodation
  • mental health and wellbeing support
  • The recovery hotline is open from 7.30am-7.30pm everyday.
Need an interpreter? Call the hotline on 1800 560 760 and press 9.
For flood and storm information and support in NSW visit nsw.gov.au/floods
If you require assistance relating to insurance matters, please call the Insurance Council Australia's disaster hotline on 1800 734 621.
Impacts in your area: 
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • For more information on road closures check the VicRoads website traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au.
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 30/10/2022 01:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV. 
  • For road closure information go to www.traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au or phone 13 11 70.
Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline. 
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.name: Emergency Warning
properties.webBody:
This Emergency Warning is being issued for parts of Echuca and Echuca Village. 
If you live, work or are holidaying in this area, you should Evacuate Immediately. 

MAJOR FLOODING AT ECHUCA AND MOAMA PEAKED AT 94.98 METRES AHD WEDNESDAY NIGHT, HIGHER THAN THE 1975 AND 1993 FLOODS

Floodwaters from the Campaspe and Goulburn Rivers combined with flows down the Murray River have caused major flooding at Echuca and Moama where the river level peaked around 94.98 metres AHD Wednesday night with major flooding, higher than the October 1993 (94.77 m AHD) and November 1975 (94.80 m AHD) flood peaks.

MURRAY RIVER
  • The Murray River at Echuca peaked at 94.98 metres AHD around 11:45 pm Wednesday and is currently at 94.95 metres AHD and falling slowly, with major flooding. 
  • The Murray River at Echuca may remain above the major flood level (94.40 metres AHD) until 05-06 November.
CAMPASPE RIVER
  • Moderate flooding is occurring along the Campaspe River downstream of Rochester. 
  • The river level along the Campaspe River at Echuca peaked at 94.86 m AHD Wednesday night. 
  • The river level is currently at 94.63 m AHD and steady, with moderate flooding. 
  • The river is expected to remain above the moderate flood level (94.40 m AHD) for the remainder of Friday and into Saturday. 
  • River levels will remain elevated due to flood waters backing up from the Murray River and are expected to continue in the coming days.
For commercial and recreational users of the Murray River: The NSW State Emergency Service have declared an emergency area on the Murray River for areas downstream of Tocumal Road Bridge to Barham Bridge under the state Emergency Services Act 1989 (NSW) (SES Act). Do not enter the emergency area. This applies to all commercial and recreational users. Visit the NSW SES website for information: https://www.ses.nsw.gov.au/news/all-news/2022/emergency-area-declared-murray-river/
If you are located in the warning areas, it is recommended you Evacuate Immediately. If you do not relocate now you may become isolated for a number of days. If you choose to stay, emergency services may not be able to help you. 

The Echuca Emergency Relief Centre (Echuca South Basketball Stadium located at 244 High street, Echuca) can be accessed by people if required.
What you should do: 

Travel to a safe location. Options include: 
  • Travel to family and friends outside of the impacted area.
  • The Echuca Emergency Relief Centre (Echuca South Basketball Stadium located at 244 High Street, Echuca) can be accessed by people if required.
  • The recommended evacuation route is via High Street Echuca
If you are travelling by car: 
  • Do not drive through floodwater. 
  • Find alternative travel routes if roads or underpasses are flooded. 
  • Be aware of driving hazards, such as mud, debris, damaged roads and fallen trees. 
  • If driving conditions are dangerous, safely pull over away from trees, drains, low lying areas and floodwater. 
If you stay:  
  • Stay inside and be aware of changing conditions. 
  • If floodwater comes inside, move to a higher point such as a kitchen bench or second story. 
  • Follow your emergency plan, if you have one. 
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation, if safe to do so. 
  • If you choose to stay, emergency services may not be able to help you.
  • Flood water is impacting sewerage systems in Echuca. Residents should limit water usage where possible-this will reduce the volume being sent to sewerage while flood levels are high.
  • Most levees are not designed for the level of flooding we are currently experiencing, so there are risks of overtopping and potential for breach or failure.
  • We urge the community to avoid being on or near the levee in Echuca township to reduce the risk of erosion and/or damage to the levee.
You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. Call Triple Zero (000) in a life threatening emergency. 

For emergency assistance from the SES, call 132 500.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Echuca village residents, if you do not relocate now you could become isolated for 10-15 days.
  • Evacuating too late or choosing to remain in your home when recommended to evacuate, is dangerous and may put your life at risk. 
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur. 
  • Areas near the affected location may lose services including power, water, sewerage and phone coverage due to flooding.
  • We are aware of discolouration in the tap water in parts of Echuca. We have confirmed the issues is the result of increased Manganese levels in the water supply, and a treatment plan for this issue is in place. Elevated Manganese levels in the water do NOT pose a risk to your health when used for drinking, bathing, cooking or cleaning. We are continuing to monitor raw water quality.
  • To prevent the sewer network being overwhelmed, we are asking all Echuca residents to minimise their use of anything that produces wastewater, including toilets, showers, baths, dishwashers and washing machines.
  • You may see animals attempting to move to higher ground, including snakes. Leave all uninjured wildlife alone and they are likely to be fatigued and stressed. If you see animals that appear to be injured or caught in floodwater, call 136 186 or advise via the wildlife emergency app.
  • For commercial and recreational users of the Murray River: NSW State Emergency Services have declared an emergency area on the Murray River for areas downstream of Tocumal Road Bridge to Barham Bridge under the state Emergency Services Act 1989 (NSW) (SES Act). Do not enter the emergency area. This applies to all commercial and recreational users. Visit the NSW SES website for information: https://www.ses.nsw.gov.au/news/all-news/2022/emergency-area-declared-murray-river/
  • For assistance call the Flood Recovery Hotline at 1800560760.
Mosquito Alert 
With the recent floods in many areas across Victoria, the risk of mosquito breeding is high. Learn more about how to protect yourself and your family at betterhealth.vic.gov.au/protect-yourself-mosquito-borne-disease. 
What you can do:
  • Cover up - wear long, loose-fitting clothing.  
  • Use repellents that contain picaridin. 
  • Use mosquito nets or insect screens. 
  • Limit activity outdoors and move indoors if possible. 
This message was issued by State Emergency Service. 

The next update is expected by 29/10/2022 06:00 pm or as the situation changes. 

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • Consequences of flooding along the Murray River will vary between NSW and Victoria. For more information relevant to your area, please check: www.ses.nsw.gov.au in NSW and www.emergency.vic.gov.au in Victoria. 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226 
  • VicEmergency app 
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods) 
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV. 
Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.   
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

Minor flooding is occurring along the Ovens River Bright to Rocky Point.

This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Avoca River to Charlton Town.

Minor flooding is occurring along the Avoca River to Charlton Town.

The Avoca River at Charlton Town is currently at 4.13 metres and slowly falling, with minor flooding. The Avoca River at Charlton Town is likely to remain above the minor flood level (4.00m) during Saturday and into Sunday.

In the 24 hours to 12pm Saturday, rainfall totals of less than 5mm were recorded in the Avoca River catchment. No significant rainfall is forecast for the remainder of Saturday, however further rainfall is forecast from late Sunday which may lead to renewed rises.

The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au
  • For more information on road closures check the VicRoads website traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
Impacts in your area: 
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Local roads may be closed.
Mosquito alert:
The risk of mosquito breeding is high. You can reduce your risk of being bitten and getting sick:
  • Cover up - wear long, loose-fitting clothing
  • Use repellents that contain picaridin or DEET
  • Use mosquito nets or insect screens
  • Limit activity outdoors and move indoors if possible.
  • Learn more about how to protect yourself and your family at https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/protect-yourself-mosquito-borne-disease
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 30/10/2022 02:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Yarra River to Millgrove.

The Yarra River catchment has recorded rainfall averaging about 17 mm in the upper part of the catchment and about 7 mm in the lower part of the catchment since 09:00 AM Friday 28 October 2022. Rainfall totals of 5-10 mm are forecast for the catchment for Saturday 29 October 2022.

Yarra River to Millgrove:
The level of the Yarra River at Millgrove is currently at 2.25 metres, exceeding the Minor Flood Level (2.00 metres) and falling. It peaked at 2.3 metres at 3.30 AM on Saturday 29 October 2022 and is expected to remain above flood levels until Saturday evening.

properties.webBody:
This Flood Watch is being issued for Glenelg River Catchment.

WIDESPREAD RENEWED RIVER RISES AND MINOR FLOODING ARE POSSIBLE FROM MONDAY AFTERNOON.   

  • A deepening low will approach from the west, expected to be located near western Bass Strait by late Sunday, extending a cold front into western Victoria. The low will then dive south of Tasmania on Monday as the front crosses eastern Victoria. Catchments in the Flood Watch area are saturated, some of which are experiencing ongoing flooding due to recent rainfall. 
  •  Widespread renewed river level rises are likely and minor flooding may develop in the watch area from Monday afternoon. Catchments with recent or existing warnings where river levels are elevated may see fast response to further rainfall and moderate flooding is possible from early next week at some locations.  
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Review your emergency plan and check your emergency kit is fully stocked, if you have one.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.

Impacts in your area: 
  • Areas around rivers and streams may be flooded.
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
  • Local roads may be closed and low bridges may be underwater.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 29/10/2022 02:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

The Bunyip River catchment has recorded rainfall averaging about 22 mm since 09:00 am Thursday 27 October 2022.

Rainfall totals of 15-25 mm are forecast for the catchment Friday 28 October 2022.

Water levels of the Bunyip River at various locations are rising in response to the rain.

Bunyip River to Iona:
  • The level of the Bunyip River at Iona is currently at 2.98 metres, exceeding the Minor Flood Level (2.10 metres) and falling. 
  • It peaked at 3.44 metres at 4.30 am Friday morning and is expected to remain above the Minor Flood Level (2.10 metres) until Saturday evening 29 October 2022.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.

properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Latrobe River Yallourn to Traralgon Creek:

MODERATE FLOODING IS LIKELY AT THOMS BRIDGE FROM SATURDAY AFTERNOON

Minor flooding is occurring across the Latrobe River catchment. Continuing rainfall activity from Monday to Friday caused stream rises across the catchment.

Showers are forecast for the remainder of Saturday, and the situation is being monitored closely.

Latrobe River Yallourn to Traralgon Creek:

Moderate flooding is likely along the Latrobe River Yallourn to Traralgon Creek.

The Latrobe River at Thoms Bridge is currently at 4.63 metres and rising, with minor flooding. The Latrobe River at Thoms Bridge is likely to reach the moderate flood level (5.00 m) Saturday afternoon. The river level may remain above the moderate flood level (5.00 m) overnight Saturday into Sunday.
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater. 
What you should do:

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
  • Rising floodwater can be dangerous. Be aware of water levels rising near you.
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:
  •  High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Heavy rainfall may lead to an increased risk of landslides be aware of fallen earth, rocks, debris or trees.
  • Boating in floodwaters is dangerous due to debris, submerged trees and other hidden dangers. 
  • Main roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 30/10/2022 02:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:

  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Seven Creeks downstream of Euroa.

MODERATE FLOODING CONTINUING AT KIALLA WEST DURING SATURDAY AND INTO SUNDAY

MINOR FLOODING EASING AT EUROA

Rainfall during Friday caused small renewed rises along the Seven Creeks, with minor flooding currently easing at Euroa. Moderate flooding is continuing at Kialla West.

Further rainfall is forecast for the Seven and Castle Creek catchments from Sunday evening which may result in renewed river level rises into next week. The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.


Seven Creeks downstream of Euroa
  • Moderate flooding is occurring along the Seven Creeks downstream of Euroa.
  • The Seven Creeks at Kialla West is currently at 5.21 metres and steady, with moderate flooding. The Seven Creeks at Kialla West may remain above the moderate flood level (5.00 m) for the remainder of Saturday and into Sunday.

Updated Community information: 
In flood-affected areas, there are now many cases of gastro (gastroenteritis, diarrhoea) causing people to get very sick.   

To prevent gastro always wash your hands after going to the toilet, before eating, preparing food, or cleaning your teeth etc. Only drink and wash, or wash clothes in known clean water.   

Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas. 
The wet ground conditions have resulted in many trees falling without warning.  If it gets windy, trees will become more unstable and deadly.  Never park, take shelter or camp under a tree.   

If you are planning to camp close to rivers or creeks DONT!    

Unexpected river rises are very likely after even small amounts of rainfall.  

Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert. Never enter floodwater.   

In the VicEmergency App, add a watch zone for your campsite and regularly check emergency broadcasters via car radio if necessary.
What you should do:

Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.

If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
Returning home:
  •  Only turn your power on at the main electrical switchboard if water has not entered the property. 
  •  If water has entered your property, do not put the power back on until the property wiring has been tested by a licensed electrician. 
  •  If any appliances have been inundated, do not plug them in or switch them on until they have been tested by a licensed electrician.
  •  For more information visit: https://esv.vic.gov.au/safety-education/emergencies/electrical-emergency/
  • Be aware of any road closures when you return.
Generators
  • If you are using a generator, do not attempt to connect it to the wiring of your home. This is dangerous and illegal.
  •  A generator should only be used outside, with an extension cord to supply power direct to appliances such as the fridge or freezer. 
  • Using a generator indoors creates a number of safety risks including the potential for carbon monoxide poisoning or a fire.   
Recovery:
  •  Flood Recovery Hotline is a single state-wide number, 1800 560 760, that Victorians impacted by the October 2022 floods can call for help or assistance with: 
  •  Register for clean up on private property; 
  •  Navigating financial and other support ;
  •  Access to temporary accommodation Mental health and wellbeing support
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
  • If you are using a generator, do not attempt to connect it to the wiring of your home. This is dangerous and illegal.   A generator should only be used outside, with an extension cord to supply power direct to appliances such as the fridge or freezer. Using a generator indoors creates a number of safety risks including the potential for carbon monoxide poisoning or a fire.  
Impacts in your area:

  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations.
  • Roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding. Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 30/10/2022 12:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Health Messaging
  • Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. 
  • Floodwaters may contain sewage and other contaminants.  Stay out of the water - skin contact with floodwater or mud can cause illness and skin infections. Cover cuts and if you are injured during your clean up; clean the wound and contact your doctor immediately.  
  • Private water supplies may also be contaminated from floodwater, debris and chemicals. If your water supply tastes, looks or smells unusual, do not use it for drinking, preparing food, and do not give it to animals.  
  • Medicines, stored at home and affected by flood water may now be unsafe and extreme caution should be taken in trying to salvage any medicines. 
  • Mosquitoes can also breed rapidly in stagnant waters. Drain any water from containers such as plant pots, tyres, buckets, and roof gutters to control mosquitos around your home.   
  • Flooding can also cause excessive mould growth which must be cleaned up before moving back to your home as it can make you sick.     
  • Flooding can cause sewage to overflow inside your home. Contact with sewage can make people sick, so contaminated areas must be cleaned and disinfected.  
  • Any damaged gas or electricity supplies need to be declared safe by a qualified electrician or plumber. 
  • Do not use a portable generator indoors, they can produce carbon monoxide gas which could build up in a confined space and make you sick or be fatal. 
  • Food safety should also be considered and ALL food that has been flood damaged should be thrown away including canned and packaged foods.   
  • It is important to look after your mental health and that of friends, family and neighbours. If at any time you are worried about your mental health or the mental health of a loved one, call Lifeline 13 11 14 or the Suicide Call Back Service on 1300 659 467.
Recovery: 
  •  Flood Recovery Hotline is a single state-wide number, 1800 560 760, that Victorians impacted by the October 2022 floods can call for help or assistance with: navigating available supports mental health and wellbeing support The recovery hotline is open from 7:30am-7:30pm everyday.   Call 1800 560 760 If your home is flooding and you need emergency assistance Call 000 If your home is about to flood Call VICSES on 132 500
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.
Register Find Unite - Red Cross 
Red Cross has opened Register.Find.Reunite. and is urging people affected by the Victorian Floods to get in touch with their families and friends. Register.Find.Reunite. helps find and reunite family, friends and loved ones during a disaster. People can register on the Red Cross website at register.redcross.org.au, or by phone at 1800 727 077.

properties.webBody:
This Flood Watch is being issued for Traralgon Creek.

WIDESPREAD RENEWED RIVER RISES AND MINOR FLOODING POSSIBLE FROM MONDAY AFTERNOON.

A deepening low will approach from the west, expected to be located near western Bass Strait by late Sunday, extending a cold front into western Victoria. 
The low will then dive south of Tasmania on Monday as the front crosses eastern Victoria, followed by another low pressure trough which will cross the state on Tuesday.

Widespread showers and storms are expected for Sunday, Monday and Tuesday.

Catchments in the Flood Watch area are saturated, some of which are experiencing ongoing flooding due to recent rainfall.

Widespread renewed river level rises are likely and minor flooding may develop in the watch area from Monday afternoon. Catchments with recent or existing warnings where river levels are elevated may see fast response to further rainfall and moderate flooding is possible from early next week at some locations.

The Bureau of Meteorology is continuing to monitor the situation and will issue catchment specific warnings as required.

Catchment likely to be affected include:

Traralgon Creek
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Areas around rivers and streams may be flooded.
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 30/10/2022 03:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

This Advice message is being issued for Lakes Entrance.

  • Due to a whale carcass at the beach, which was first located last week, there could be an increase in shark activity.
  • A whale carcass can attract sharks to the area and mean they are closer to the shore than normal.
  • While it is not uncommon for sharks to be present off the Victorian coast, you should exercise additional caution in the area.
  • The carcass was originally located in Marlo, but as of 21/10/2022, it has broken up and spread out along the coast between Lake Tyers Beach and Lakes Entrance.
  • This is an update, replacing the Advice issued on Monday at 3.15pm.
Avoid the area. Stay informed and do not enter the water at closed beaches.
What you should do:

  • If you see sharks, report the sighting by calling Triple Zero (000) or notify lifesavers immediately if you are at a patrolled beach.
Staying safe at nearby beaches:
  • Always swim, dive or surf with a friend.
  • Swim between the red and yellow flags on patrolled beaches.
  • Don't swim in places where human or animal waste enters the water.
  • Keep away from large schools of fish, seals or other wildlife as these can attract sharks.
Impacts in your area:
  • The Victorian Fisheries Authority is monitoring for shark sightings and providing advice to relevant authorities. 
This message was issued by VFA.

The next update is expected by 02/11/2022 11:00 am or as the situation changes.

This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Loddon River Loddon Weir to Kerang.

Minor to moderate flooding is continuing along the Loddon River. The main flood peak is now approaching Appin South, where moderate flooding is occurring.

  • Moderate flooding is occurring along the Loddon River Loddon Weir to Kerang.
  • The Loddon River at Downstream (D/S) Loddon Weir is currently at 5.33m and falling slowly, with minor flooding.
  • The Loddon River at Appin South is currently at 3.15m and rising slowly, with moderate flooding. The Loddon River at Appin South is expected to remain above the moderate flood level (3.10m) for the next few days. The river level may reach around 3.20m overnight Sunday into Monday.
  • The Loddon River at MV Hwy Bridge fell below the moderate flood level Friday night and is currently at 77.45m Australian Height Datum (AHD) and falling slowly, with minor flooding The Loddon River at MV Hwy Bridge is expected to remain above the minor flood level (77.00m) for the next few days.
In the 24 hours to 10am Saturday, rainfall totals of up to 5mm were recorded in the upper Loddon River catchment. No significant rainfall is forecast for the remainder of Saturday. The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater. 
What you should do:
  • Check you have enough food, drinking water and medications.
  • Rising floodwater can be dangerous. Be aware of water levels rising near you.
  • If you are camping close to a creek or river, you may be at risk of flooding and need to move to higher ground, away from waterways.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - do not drive through floodwater. Do not overestimate the capability of your vehicle. It doesnt take much to make your car become unstable, lose traction or wash away.
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around and find a safe alternative route. Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
Community newsletter 
A community newsletter for Gannawarra Shire has been developed to assist with any questions locals may have. Go to: Community Newsletter - Gannawarra Shire.
Impacts in your area:
  • A number of local and arterial roads are closed due to floodwater. For more information on road closures go to VicTraffic. 
  • Some areas are likely to lose services including power, water, sewerage and telephone due to flooding.
  • Be aware that snakes may look for shelter and food inside houses, storage sheds and other buildings near floodwater. Damaged structures and debris are more accessible to snakes.
Mosquito alert:
The risk of mosquito breeding is high. You can reduce your risk of being bitten and getting sick:
  • Cover up - wear long, loose-fitting clothing
  • Use repellents that contain picaridin or DEET
  • Use mosquito nets or insect screens
  • Limit activity outdoors and move indoors if possible.
  • Learn more about how to protect yourself and your family at https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/protect-yourself-mosquito-borne-disease
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 30/10/2022 01:00 pm or as the situation changes.

properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for the Broken Creek at Walshs Bridge

Updated Community information: link to Community Update on Youtube click on or follow this link     https://youtu.be/Bpj53qw6las


  • In flood-affected areas, there are now many cases of gastro (gastroenteritis, diarrhoea) causing people to get very sick.  
To prevent gastro always wash your hands after going to the toilet, before eating, preparing food, or cleaning your teeth etc. Only drink and wash, or wash clothes in known clean water.

Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas. 

  • Virtual Community Meeting: Based on community feedback, the face-to-face community information meeting planned for Nathalia this afternoon has been changed to a virtual meeting recorded and shared via Youtube link, Facebook etc out to communities. 
SES aims to have the recording of the meeting out to community later today. Speakers include: the Incident Controller, Police, and the Goulburn Broken Catchment Management Authority (GBCMA).
If you receive the meeting link or Facebook post, please watch and share the information with others that may not have social media or internet access.


MODERATE FLOODING EASING ALONG THE BROKEN CREEK AT WALSHS BRIDGE OVERNIGHT FRIDAY INTO SATURDAY

A MINOR FLOOD PEAK AT NATHALIA POSSIBLE OVERNIGHT FRIDAY INTO SATURDAY

  • Moderate flooding is easing along the Broken Creek at Walshs Bridge overnight Friday into Saturday. 
  • Minor flooding is expected to continue at Nathalia with a minor flood peak possible overnight Friday into Saturday.
  • Creek levels around Numurkah peaked overnight Monday into Tuesday, and creek levels remain elevated.
  • In the 24 hours to 9:00 am Friday, no significant rainfall has been observed across the Broken Creek catchment. 
  • Showers are forecast for Friday and into Saturday.
  • The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.
Broken Creek:
  • Moderate flooding is easing along the Broken Creek.
  • The Broken Creek at Walshs Bridge peaked at 3.11 at 7:00 pm Wednesday and is currently at 3.06 metres and falling slowly, with moderate flooding. The river level is likely to ease below the moderate flood level (3.00 m) overnight Friday into Saturday.
  • The Broken Creek at Nathalia is currently at 2.21 metres and rising slowly, with minor flooding. The Broken Creek at Nathalia is likely to peak near 2.30 metres overnight Friday into Saturday. The river level is expected to remain above the minor flood level (1.50 m) for the next few days.

Prepare for creek rises and flooding now. Take actions to protect your life and property against potential hazards caused by flooding.
What you should do:

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Farmers should move livestock and machinery to higher ground, if still safe to do so. 
  • Be prepared to move important household items to higher ground, on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds. 
  • Follow your emergency plan and locate your emergency kit, if you have one.
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation.
  • If you are camping close to a creek or river, you may be at risk of flooding and need to move to higher ground, away from waterways.
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area may include:
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations.
  • Very polluted, dirty water with lots of toilet sewage waste and animal manure (poo) is spreading across this area from the Barmah direction. Follow the health advice below especially about cuts treatment.
  • The Nathalia to Katamatite Road is open today, however, there are many roads in this area closed by floodwater. Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.  (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
At Nathalia (note that most of the demountable flood barriers were recently installed to be in place and ready for use)
At:
  • 2.0 m at Nathalia Town Gauge /1.3 m at  Walshs Bridge= Minor flood level
  • 1.72 m at Nathalia / 2.55 m at Walshs = Dec 2010 flood level, low lying land and roads beside the creek flooded
  • 2.2 m at Nathalia / 2.95 m at Walshs = Flooding to the lowest part of Weir Street likely

  • 2.5  at Nathalia / 3.0 m at Walshs = Moderate flood level
  • 2.6 m at Nathalia =  Drain 13 channel spillway will begin operating around this level with  flow path to the north west
  • 2.8 m at Nathalia  /  3.3 m at Walshs =  Demountable flood barriers in place along Weir Street, west of Murray Valley Highway Bridge near fire station to the public toilets
  • 2.82 m at Nathalia / 3.35 m Walshs  =  flood barriers in place across Railway Street closing road access

Health Messaging 

  • Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. 
  • Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas. 
  • Stay out of the water - skin contact with floodwater or mud can cause illness and skin infections. Cover cuts and if you are injured during your clean up; clean the wound and contact your doctor immediately.  
  • Private water supplies may also be contaminated from floodwater, debris and chemicals. If your water supply tastes, looks or smells unusual, do not use it for drinking, preparing food, and do not give it to animals.  
  • Medicines, stored at home and affected by flood water may now be unsafe and extreme caution should be taken in trying to salvage any medicines. 
  • Mosquitoes can also breed rapidly in stagnant waters. Drain any water from containers such as plant pots, tyres, buckets, and roof gutters to control mosquitos around your home. 
  • Flooding can also cause excessive mould growth which must be cleaned up before moving back to your home as it can make you sick. 
  • Any damaged gas or electricity supplies need to be declared safe by a qualified electrician or plumber. 
  • Do not use a portable generator indoors, they can produce carbon monoxide gas which could build up in a confined space and make you sick or be fatal. 
  • Food safety should also be considered and ALL food that has been flood damaged should be thrown away, including canned and packaged foods. 
  • It is important to look after your mental health and that of friends, family and neighbours. If at any time you are worried about your mental health or the mental health of a loved one, call Lifeline 13 11 14 or the Suicide Call Back Service on 1300 659 467.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 29/10/2022 04:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

This is a Final Minor Flood Warning for Mt Emu Creek Skipton. 

MINOR FLOODING HAS EASED ALONG THE MT EMU CREEK AT SKIPTON   

  • The Mt Emu Creek at Skipton peaked around the minor flood level during Friday evening and river levels are now falling.   No significant rainfall is forecast for the remainder of Saturday and into Sunday.     
  •  Forecast rainfall from Sunday afternoon and into early next week may cause renewed river level rises and areas of minor flooding. The situation is being closely monitored, and further flood warnings will be issued if necessary.
  • The Mt Emu Creek at Skipton is currently at 3.72 metres and falling, below the minor flood level.
The threat of flooding is reduced. Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and beware of hazards remaining in the warning area.
What you should do:

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.

If your home or business has been flooded:
  • Check for building damage before you enter.
  • Have all electrical and gas equipment professionally tested before use.
  • Clean and dry out the building as soon as possible.

Call Triple Zero (000) in a life threatening emergency. For emergency assistance from the SES call 132 500.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Damage to roads and buildings caused by flooding may still exist in your area. 
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

This will be the last warning for this flood.

properties.webBody:
This Flood Watch is being issued for the Upper Murray and Mitta Mitta River Catchment.

Widespread renewed river rises and minor flooding possible from Monday afternoon.

A deepening low will approach from the west on Sunday, expected to be located near western Bass Strait by evening with a cold front extending into western Victoria. The low will then dive south of Tasmania on Monday as the front moves over eastern Victoria, followed by another low pressure trough which will cross the state on Tuesday.

Widespread showers and storms are expected for Sunday, Monday and Tuesday.

Catchments in the flood watch area are saturated, some of which are experiencing ongoing flooding due to recent rainfall.

Widespread renewed river level rises are likely and minor flooding may develop in the watch area from Monday afternoon. Catchments with recent or existing warnings where river levels are elevated may see fast response to further rainfall and moderate flooding is possible from early next week at some locations.

Minor Flood Warnings are in place for the below sub-catchments:
  • Murray River Biggara to Bringenbrong
  • Murray River Bringenbrong to Lake Hume
  • Mitta Mitta River downstream of Lake Dartmouth
  • Tallangatta Creek
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
Impacts in your area: 
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 30/10/2022 03:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Minor flooding is occurring along the Swampy Plains River at Khancoban Pondage and along the Murray River at Bringenbrong. Minor flooding may develop at Jingellic during Saturday evening, with a peak around the minor flood level possible overnight Saturday into Sunday.

Snowy Hydro advise that the releases from Khancoban Pondage are continuing above the minor flood level during Saturday.

Murray River Biggara to Bringenbrong

properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for the King River.

Moderate Flooding continuing at Docker Road Bridge.

Moderate flooding is occurring along the King River at Docker Rd Bridge with minor flooding at downstream of Lake William Hovell . Minor flooding is also occurring along the Ovens River at Wangaratta. Further rises are expected along the Ovens River at Wangaratta where moderate flooding is likely to develop from Saturday afternoon as upstream floodwaters arrive.

In the 24 hours to 9:00 am Saturday rainfall totals of up to 25 mm have been observed across the Ovens and King River catchment. No significant rainfall is forecast for the remainder of Saturday.

King River
  • The King River downstream of Lake William Hovell is currently at 2.00 metres and steady, with minor flooding. It is likely to remain above the minor flood level (1.80 m) during Saturday.
  • The King River at Docker Rd Bridge is currently peaking around 4.05 metres, with moderate flooding. It is expected to remain above the moderate flood level (3.95 m) overnight Saturday into Sunday.
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater. 
What you should do:
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • If you are camping close to a creek or river, you may be at risk of flooding and need to move to higher ground, away from waterways.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/

If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Low lying agricultural areas may be flooded
  • The Docker-Carbour Road is closed between Wangaratta-Whitfield Road and Oxley-Meadow Creek Road.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 29/10/2022 06:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:

  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226

properties.webBody:
This Flood Watch is being issued for Campaspe Barnadown to Rochester.

Information relevant to Rochester Township will be issued within this message for Barnadown to Rochester. The separate Rochester Township advice message will no longer be issued. 

  • Moderate flooding is continuing along the Campaspe River at Echuca. 
  • In the 24 hours to 9:00 am Saturday, rainfall totals of up to 10 mm have been recorded in the Campaspe River catchment. 
  • Showers are forecast for the next few days. The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary

The latest community newsletter from Saturday 29 October is available here: Community newsletter
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Local roads may be closed and low bridges may be underwater.
  • Areas around rivers and streams may be flooded.
  • You may see animals attempting to move to higher ground, including snakes.
  • Leave all uninjured wildlife alone and they are likely to be fatigued and stressed.
  • If you see animals that appear to e injured or caught in floodwater, call 136 186 or advise via the wildlife emergency app.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 30/10/2022 11:00 am or as the situation changes.

Mosquito Alert    
With the recent floods in many areas across Victoria, the risk of mosquito breeding is high. Learn more about how to protect yourself and your family at https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/protect-yourself-mosquito-borne-disease
What you can do:
  • Cover up - wear long, loose-fitting clothing.  
  • Use repellents that contain picaridin. 
  • Use mosquito nets or insect screens. 
  • Limit activity outdoors and move indoors if possible. 

Flood Recovery Hotline - Call 1800 560 760
Flood Recovery Hotline is a single state-wide number, 1800 560 760, that Victorians impacted by the October 2022 floods can call for help or assistance with:
  • navigating available supports
  • clean-up
  • temporary accommodation
  • mental health and wellbeing support
The recovery hotline is open from 7.30am-7.30pm everyday.
Need an interpreter? Call the hotline on 1800 560 760 and press 9.
For flood and storm information and support in NSW visit nsw.gov.au/floods
If you require assistance relating to insurance matters, please call the Insurance Council Australia's disaster hotline on 1800 734 621.

  • If your buildings have been impacted by flood waters you should have your property inspected by a registered electrician. Visit the Energy Safe Victoria site for more: https://esv.vic.gov.au/safety-education/emergencies/energy-safety-during-floods/
  • For more information on any assistance you need, visit emergency.vic.gov.au/relief/#relief_assistance
Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Yarra River from Coldstream to Warrandyte.

The Yarra River catchment has recorded rainfall averaging about 17 mm in the upper part of the catchment and about 7 mm in the lower part of the catchment since 09:00 AM Friday 28 October 2022. Rainfall totals of 5-10 mm are forecast for the catchment for Saturday 29 October 2022.

The level of the Yarra River at Christmas Hills is currently at 3.82 metres, exceeding the Minor Flood Level (3.00 metres) and rising. It is expected to peak above the Minor Flood Level (3.00 metres) on Saturday 29 October 2022.

The level of the Yarra River at Warrandyte is currently at 3.40 metres, exceeding the Minor Flood Level (3.00 metres) and rising. It peaked at 3.4 metres at 11 PM Thursday 27 October and is expected to peak again above the Minor Flood Level (3.00 metres) on Saturday 29 October 2022.

Yarra River from Coldstream to Warrandyte:

The level of the Yarra River at Yarra Glen is currently at 4.76 metres, exceeding the Moderate Flood Level (4.60 metres) and steady. It is currently peaking and is expected to remain above the Moderate Flood Level (5.10 metres) until Sunday 30 October 2022.
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater.

  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations.
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.

Roads that may be impacted by flooding of the Yarra River in Yarra Glen include:

Minor flooding is occurring at Mongans Bridge, Kiewa Main Stream and Bandiana.

In the 24 hours to 09:00 am Friday, widespread rainfall totals of 10-20 mm were recorded in the Kiewa River catchment. Isolated higher totals of up to 60 mm were recorded upstream in the catchment. Further rainfall is forecast for the remainder of Friday.

Kiewa River downstream of Mongans Bridge:
  • The Kiewa River at Kiewa (Main Stream) is currently at 3.32 metres and steady, with minor flooding. It is likely to remain above the minor flood level (3.30 m) for the remainder of Friday and into Saturday.
  • The Kiewa River at Bandiana is currently at 2.98 metres and steady, with minor flooding. It is expected to remain above the minor flood level (2.80 m) over the next few days.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
  • Local roads may be closed and low bridges may be underwater.

This Flood Watch is being issued for Latrobe River upstream of Yallourn.

WIDESPREAD RENEWED RIVER RISES AND MINOR FLOODING POSSIBLE FROM MONDAY AFTERNOON.

A deepening low will approach from the west, expected to be located near western Bass Strait by late Sunday, extending a cold front into western Victoria. The low will then dive south of Tasmania on Monday as the front crosses eastern Victoria, followed by another low pressure trough which will cross the state on Tuesday.

Widespread showers and storms are expected for Sunday, Monday and Tuesday.

Catchments in the Flood Watch area are saturated, some of which are experiencing ongoing flooding due to recent rainfall.

Widespread renewed river level rises are likely and minor flooding may develop in the watch area from Monday afternoon. Catchments with recent or existing warnings where river levels are elevated may see fast response to further rainfall and moderate flooding is possible from early next week at some locations.

Catchment likely to be affected include:

Latrobe River
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.

This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for the Hughes Creek.

MODERATE FLOODING EXPECTED AT DOWNSTREAM LAKE EILDON SATURDAY MORNING
MODERATE FLOODING POSSIBLE AT SEYMOUR SUNDAY MORNING 
MINOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT DOWNSTREAM LAKE EILDON, TAGGERTY, SEYMOUR, MURCHISON, SHEPPARTON AND MCCOYS BRIDGE   

Moderate flooding is expected at Downstream Lake Eildon during Saturday morning and may develop along the Goulburn River at Seymour during Sunday morning.  
Minor flooding is currently occurring along the Goulburn River catchment at Downstream Lake Eildon, Taggerty, Seymour, Murchison, Shepparton and McCoys Bridge. 
Goulburn Murray Water has advised that releases from Lake Eildon will be increasing from the current 24,000 ML/d up to around 30,000 ML/d by Saturday late morning. The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.

Updated Community information:
In flood-affected areas, there are now many cases of gastro (gastroenteritis, diarrhoea) causing people to get very sick.   
 To prevent gastro always wash your hands after going to the toilet, before eating, preparing food, or cleaning your teeth etc. Only drink and wash, or wash clothes in known clean water.   
 Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas. 
The wet ground conditions have resulted in many trees falling without warning.  If it gets windy, trees will become more unstable and deadly.  Never park, take shelter or camp under a tree.   

If you are planning to camp close to rivers or creeks DONT!    

Unexpected river rises are very likely after even small amounts of rainfall and ongoing water releases from Lake Eildon.   

Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert. Never enter floodwater.   

In the VicEmergency App, add a watch zone for your campsite and regularly check emergency broadcasters via car radio if necessary.
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
When returning home 
  • Only turn your power on at the main electrical switchboard if water has not entered the property.  
  • If water has entered your property, do not put the power back on until the property wiring has been tested by a licensed electrician.  
  • If any appliances have been inundated, do not plug them in or switch them on until they have been tested by a licensed electrician.  
  • For more information visit: https://esv.vic.gov.au/safety-education/emergencies/electrical-emergency/ 
  • If cleaning after damage has occurred, protect your health and safety. 
  • Protect your lungs by wearing a N95 or P2 mask.  
  • Wear strong boots, gloves and protective clothing and wash your hands and clothes regularly.  
  • Stagnant water can be harmful to your health. Dont swim, drink or wash in stagnant water.  
  • Smelly black water can be reported to EPA on 1800 560 760


Impacts in your area: 

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
  • Local roads may be closed and low bridges may be underwater.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 29/10/2022 06:30 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline. 
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.
Recovery: 
Flood Recovery Hotline is a single state-wide number, 1800 560 760, that Victorians impacted by the October 2022 floods can call for help or assistance with: 
  • Register for clean up on private property; 
  • Navigating financial and other support 
  • Access to temporary accommodation 
  • Mental health and wellbeing support 
The recovery hotline is open from 7:30am-7:30pm everyday.   Call 1800 560 760 or visit www.erv.vic.gov.au for further information. 

For life-threatening emergencies, call Triple Zero (000) immediately. 
For emergency assistance during floods call 132 500 for SES assistance.

Health Messaging 
  • Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. 
  • Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.    
  • Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas. Stay out of the water - skin contact with floodwater or mud can cause illness and skin infections. Cover cuts and if you are injured during your clean up; clean the wound and contact your doctor immediately.  
  • Private water supplies may also be contaminated from floodwater, debris and chemicals. If your water supply tastes, looks or smells unusual, do not use it for drinking, preparing food, and do not give it to animals.  
  • Medicines, stored at home and affected by flood water may now be unsafe and extreme caution should be taken in trying to salvage any medicines. 
  • Mosquitoes can also breed rapidly in stagnant waters. Drain any water from containers such as plant pots, tyres, buckets, and roof gutters to control mosquitos around your home. 
  • Flooding can also cause excessive mould growth which must be cleaned up before moving back to your home as it can make you sick. 
  • Any damaged gas or electricity supplies need to be declared safe by a qualified electrician or plumber. 
  • Do not use a portable generator indoors, they can produce carbon monoxide gas which could build up in a confined space and make you sick or be fatal. 
  • Food safety should also be considered and ALL food that has been flood damaged should be thrown away, including canned and packaged foods. 
  • It is important to look after your mental health and that of friends, family and neighbours. If at any time you are worried about your mental health or the mental health of a loved one, call Lifeline 13 11 14 or the Suicide Call Back Service on 1300 659 467.

Register Find Unite - Red Cross 
Red Cross has opened Register.Find.Reunite. and is urging people affected by the Victorian Floods to get in touch with their families and friends. Register.Find.Reunite. helps find and reunite family, friends and loved ones during a disaster. People can register on the Red Cross website at register.redcross.org.au, or by phone at 1800 727 077.

properties.webBody:
This Flood Advice is being issued for Loddon River downstream of Kerang.

River levels are elevated along the Loddon River downstream of Kerang.

  • Flooding from the Murray River and Loddon River is impacting buildings and roads in the Murrabit West area. These include Salau Road, Dawe Road, Flowerday Lane and sections of Murrabit West Road.
  • Catchments in the Flood Watch area are saturated, some of which are experiencing ongoing flooding due to recent rainfall.
  • Catchments where river levels are elevated may see fast response to further rainfall and moderate flooding is possible from early next week at some locations.
In the 24 hours to 10am Saturday, rainfall totals of up to 5mm were recorded in the upper Loddon River catchment. No significant rainfall is forecast for the remainder of Saturday. The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater. 
What you should do:
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
  • Stay informed - listen to emergency broadcasters and monitor warnings.
Impacts in your area:
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations.
  • Check the VicTraffic website for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 30/10/2022 01:00 pm or as the situation changes.

properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Murray River downstream of Barham to Wentworth.

Floodwaters from the Campaspe and Goulburn Rivers combined with flows down the Murray River have caused major flooding at Echuca and Moama where the river level peaked around 94.98m AHD Wednesday night with major flooding, higher than the October 1993 (94.77m AHD) and November 1975 (94.80m AHD) flood peaks.

Major flooding is possible along the Murray River at Swan Hill. Moderate flooding is occurring at Wakool Junction. Minor flooding is occurring at Boundary Bend and Wentworth, with moderate flooding possible. Minor flooding is possible at Euston. Moderate flooding may occur at Mildura.

  • The Murray River at Swan Hill is likely to exceed the minor flood level (4.50m) over the weekend and may reach the major flood level (4.70m) during the second week of November (8 to 11 November). This is similar to the October 1993 flood event.
  • The Murray River at Wakool Junction may reach around 11.40m 20 to 23 November, with moderate flooding.
  • The Murray River at Boundary Bend may exceed the moderate flood level (8.50m) over the weekend. The river level may reach around 8.70m 24 to 26 November, with moderate flooding.
  • The Murray River at Euston may exceed the minor flood level (9.10m) in mid November. The river level may reach around 9.50m 25 to 27 November, with minor flooding.
  • The Murray River at Mildura Weir may exceed the minor flood level (36.00m AHD) around 10 to 12 November. The river level may reach 37.50m AHD round the end of November, with moderate flooding, similar to the 1993 flood.
Further rainfall is forecast for the reminder of Friday across parts of the Murray River Basin and another trough may bring showers and thunderstorm during Monday and Tuesday, which may cause renewed river level rises and flooding. The situation is being closely monitored and revised predictions will be provided if necessary.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels online by visiting www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings website.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - do not drive through floodwater. Do not overestimate the capability of your vehicle. It doesnt take much to make your car become unstable, lose traction or wash away.
Community newsletter 
A community newsletter for Swan Hill has been developed to assist with any questions locals may have. Go to: Community Newsletter - Swan Hill.
Impacts in your area: 
  • High river levels may cause flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Some agricultural land may be vulnerable to flooding. Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Local roads may be closed.
  • Consequences of flooding along the Murray River vary between NSW and Victoria. For more information relevant to your area please check https://www.ses.nsw.gov.au/ in New South Wales and https://www.emergency.vic.gov.au/ in Victoria.
Murray River Closure:
the Murray River is closed to river craft downstream of Tocumwal Bridge to Robinvale.  People and boats are prohibited from entering the river between these locations. Any person on the Murray between these points are to leave the river.  This declaration applies to all residents on both sides of the border.  Neither NSW or Victorian users are permitted on the river at this time.

Covid safety: 
If you need to seek support from an Emergency Relief Centre and you are Covid positive, or suspect you may have been exposed, please consider wearing a mask and maintaining 1.5m distance from others, where possible.

Blackwater event:  Significant rainfall and flooding can cause water quality issues like low-oxygen (hypoxic) blackwater and blue green algae. High levels of organic matter have been washed into waterways and, combined with warm weather, can cause oxygen levels in the water to drop. This can harm or cause the death of fish and crayfish. River managers and scientists monitor rivers for water quality issues and work to reduce the impacts of a blackwater event where they can. Low levels of dissolved oxygen are recorded at several locations across northern Victoria and in the Murray River. The scale of the current flooding means water quality will not improve quickly. Any fish death event in Victoria should be reported to the EPA by calling 1300 372 842.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.
The next update is expected by 29/10/2022 05:30 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app

- The Murray River at Boundary Bend may exceed the moderate flood level (8.50m) over the weekend. The river level may reach around 8.70m 24 to 26 November, with moderate flooding.
- The Murray River at Euston may exceed the minor flood level (9.10m) in mid November. The river level may reach around 9.50m 25 to 27 November, with minor flooding.
- The Murray River at Mildura Weir may exceed the minor flood level (36.00m AHD) around 10 to 12 November. The river level may reach 37.50m AHD round the end of November, with moderate flooding, similar to the 1993 flood. 

Further rainfall is forecast for the reminder of Friday across parts of the Murray River Basin and another trough may bring showers and thunderstorm during Monday and Tuesday, which may cause renewed river level rises and flooding. The situation is being closely monitored and revised predictions will be provided if necessary. 

Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
