properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Goulburn River Seymour to Shepparton.

Updated Community information:   

  •  In flood-affected areas, there are now many cases of gastro (gastroenteritis, diarrhoea) causing people to get very sick.   
 To prevent gastro always wash your hands after going to the toilet, before eating, preparing food, or cleaning your teeth etc. Only drink and wash, or wash clothes in known clean water.   

MINOR FLOODING CURRENTLY OCCURRING AT DOWNSTREAM of LAKE EILDON, including at TAGGERTY, SEYMOUR, MURCHISON, SHEPPARTON AND MCCOYS BRIDGE 

MODERATE FLOODING EXPECTED AT DOWNSTREAM of LAKE EILDON SATURDAY MORNING  
MODERATE FLOODING POSSIBLE AT SEYMOUR SUNDAY MORNING    

  • Minor flooding is currently occurring along the Goulburn River catchment at Downstream  of Lake Eildon, Taggerty, Seymour, Murchison, Shepparton and McCoys Bridge. 
  • Goulburn Murray Water has advised that releases from Lake Eildon will be increasing from the current 24,000 ML/d up to around 30,000 ML/d by Saturday late morning.  
  • The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.  
  • Moderate flooding is expected at Downstream of Lake Eildon during Saturday morning and may develop along the Goulburn River at Seymour during Sunday morning.   
Goulburn River Seymour to Shepparton:  
  • Minor flooding is occurring along the Goulburn River Seymour to Shepparton.  
  • The Goulburn River at Murchison is currently around the minor flood level (9.00 m) and steady. 
  • The Goulburn River at Murchison is expected to remain around the minor flood level (9.00 m) during Saturday and into Sunday.  
  • Note that the Murchison Bridge is still limited to small vehicles only, no large trucks or farm machinery.
  • The Goulburn River at Shepparton  is currently at 10.51 metres and falling, with minor flooding.  The Goulburn River at Shepparton is expected to remain above the minor flood level (9.50 m) during Saturday and into Sunday.

 Goulburn River Lake Eildon to Seymour:  
  • Moderate flooding may occur along the Goulburn River Lake Eildon to Seymour.  
  • Minor flooding is currently occurring at Trawool. 
  • River levels are rising and are expected to remain above the minor flood level during Saturday and into Sunday.  
  • The Goulburn River downstream of Lake Eildon is currently at 3.81 metres and steady, with minor flooding.  The Goulburn River downstream of Lake Eildon is expected to exceed the moderate flood level (4.00 m) Saturday morning.  The river level is likely to reach around 4.40 metres late Saturday morning.  
  • The Goulburn River at Seymour  is currently at 4.56 metres and steady, with minor flooding.  The Goulburn River at Seymour may reach the moderate flood level (5.20 m) Sunday morning.    
 Goulburn River downstream of Shepparton:  
  • Please note The Murray Valley Highway is fully closed at Mc Coys Bridge due to Bridge damage. 
  • Minor flooding is occurring along the Goulburn River downstream of Shepparton.  
  • The Goulburn River at McCoys Bridge is currently at 9.93 metres and steady, below the moderate flood level (10.00 m).  The Goulburn River at McCoys Bridge is expected to remain above the minor flood level (9.00 m) during Saturday and Sunday.   


Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.

Be aware of the increased likelihood of trees falling due to the very wet ground, especially in windy conditions. Never shelter, park or set up campsites under trees.

If you are planning to camp or go bush driving close to rivers or creeks this long weekend, DON'T!   

Unexpected and rapid river and creek levels are very likely even with small amounts of rain and ongoing water releases from Lake Eildon dam.   

Support the local towns and make sure to set a watch zone for your location this long weekend and regularly check emergency radio broadcasters (ABC or UGFM radio) via your car radio if necessary.  
What you should do: 

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.
  • Don't go fishing, kayaking, or boating. Floodwaters is dangerous due to debris, submerged trees and other hidden dangers. 
  • If cleaning after damage has occurred, protect your health and safety.
  • Protect your lungs by wearing a N95 or P2 mask. 
  • Wear strong boots, gloves and protective clothing and wash your hands and clothes regularly. 
  • Stagnant water can be harmful to your health. Dont swim, drink or wash in stagnant water. 
  • Smelly black water can be reported to EPA on 1800 560 760
If returning home
  • Only turn your power on at the main electrical switchboard if water has not entered the property. 
  • If water has entered your property, do not put the power back on until the property wiring has been tested by a licensed electrician. 
  • If any appliances have been inundated, do not plug them in or switch them on until they have been tested by a licensed electrician. 
  • For more information visit: https://esv.vic.gov.au/safety-education/emergencies/electrical-emergency/
Impacts in your area: 

  • Smelly black water can be reported to EPA on 1800 560 760
  • Stagnant water can be harmful to your health. Dont swim, drink or wash in stagnant water. 
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Local roads may be closed and low bridges may be underwater.
  • Please note that Regional Roads Victoria have advised that the Murchison Bridge on the Murchison-Violet Town Road (High Road) is open to light vehicles only. NO TRUCKS OR HEAVY AGRICULTURE MACHINERY. 
  • For more information on road closures check the VicRoads website traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au.
  • Don't go fishing, kayaking, or boating. Floodwaters is dangerous due to debris, submerged trees and other hidden dangers. 
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 29/10/2022 06:30 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline. 
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.  
Recovery:
Flood Recovery Hotline is a single state-wide number, 1800 560 760, that Victorians impacted by the October 2022 floods can call for help or assistance with:
  • Register for clean up on private property; 
  • Navigating financial and other support
  • Access to temporary accommodation 
  • Mental health and wellbeing support 
The recovery hotline is open from 7:30am-7:30pm everyday.   Call 1800 560 760 or visit www.erv.vic.gov.au for further information. 

For life-threatening emergencies, call Triple Zero (000) immediately. 
For emergency assistance during floods call 132 500 for SES assistance.

Health Messaging
  • Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. 
  • Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas. 
  • Stay out of the water - skin contact with floodwater or mud can cause illness and skin infections. Cover cuts and if you are injured during your clean up; clean the wound and contact your doctor immediately.  
  • Private water supplies may also be contaminated from floodwater, debris and chemicals. If your water supply tastes, looks or smells unusual, do not use it for drinking, preparing food, and do not give it to animals.  
  • Medicines, stored at home and affected by flood water may now be unsafe and extreme caution should be taken in trying to salvage any medicines. 
  • Mosquitoes can also breed rapidly in stagnant waters. Drain any water from containers such as plant pots, tyres, buckets, and roof gutters to control mosquitos around your home. 
  • Flooding can also cause excessive mould growth which must be cleaned up before moving back to your home as it can make you sick. 
  • Any damaged gas or electricity supplies need to be declared safe by a qualified electrician or plumber. 
  • Do not use a portable generator indoors, they can produce carbon monoxide gas which could build up in a confined space and make you sick or be fatal. 
  • Food safety should also be considered and ALL food that has been flood damaged should be thrown away, including canned and packaged foods. 
  • It is important to look after your mental health and that of friends, family and neighbours. If at any time you are worried about your mental health or the mental health of a loved one, call Lifeline 13 11 14 or the Suicide Call Back Service on 1300 659 467.
Register Find Unite - Red Cross 
Red Cross has opened Register.Find.Reunite. and is urging people affected by the Victorian Floods to get in touch with their families and friends. Register.Find.Reunite. helps find and reunite family, friends and loved ones during a disaster. People can register on the Red Cross website at register.redcross.org.au, or by phone at 1800 727 077.

properties.webBody:
This Major Flood Warning is being issued for Wharparilla area.. 

Flooding has impacted residents in the area of Glyn Road, Wharparilla. 

Flooding is expected to remain at current levels for the next week.

The latest community newsletter from Saturday 29 October is available here: Community newsletter
Move to higher ground. Act now - immediately take actions to protect your life and property.
What you should do: 
Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater. 
Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary. 

If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around and find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.     
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow. 
Stay informed - listen to emergency broadcasters and monitor warnings.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in many locations. 
  • A small number of properties are likely to be impacted in or around Glyn Road Wharparilla.
  • Roads around the Glyn Road Wharparilla area may be be impacted.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service. 

The next update is expected by 30/10/2022 10:00 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au

This Flood Watch is being issued for Morwell River.

WIDESPREAD RENEWED RIVER RISES AND MINOR FLOODING POSSIBLE FROM MONDAY AFTERNOON.

A deepening low will approach from the west, expected to be located near western Bass Strait by late Sunday, extending a cold front into western Victoria. The low will then dive south of Tasmania on Monday as the front crosses eastern Victoria, followed by another low pressure trough which will cross the state on Tuesday.

Widespread showers and storms are expected for Sunday, Monday and Tuesday.

Catchments in the Flood Watch area are saturated, some of which are experiencing ongoing flooding due to recent rainfall.

Widespread renewed river level rises are likely and minor flooding may develop in the watch area from Monday afternoon. Catchments with recent or existing warnings where river levels are elevated may see fast response to further rainfall and moderate flooding is possible from early next week at some locations.

Catchment likely to be affected include:

Latrobe River
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Areas around rivers and streams may be flooded.
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 30/10/2022 03:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226

  • The Goulburn River at Murchison is currently around the minor flood level (9.00 m) and steady. The Goulburn River at Murchison is expected to remain around the minor flood level (9.00 m) during Saturday and into Sunday. 
The Goulburn River at Shepparton 
  • is currently at 10.51 metres and falling, with minor flooding. 
  • The Goulburn River at Shepparton is expected to remain above the minor flood level (9.50 m) during Saturday and into Sunday. 
Goulburn River downstream of Shepparton: 
  • Please note The Murray Valley Highway is fully closed at Mc Coys Bridge due to Bridge damage.
  • Minor flooding is occurring along the Goulburn River downstream of Shepparton. 
  •  The Goulburn River at McCoys Bridge is currently at 9.93 metres and steady, below the moderate flood level (10.00 m). 
  • The Goulburn River at McCoys Bridge is expected to remain above the minor flood level (9.00 m) during Saturday and Sunday.
Prepare for flooding now. Take actions to protect your life and property against potential hazards caused by flooding.

If you are planning to camp or go bush driving close to rivers or creeks this long weekend, DON'T!

Unexpected and rapid river and creek levels are very likely even with small amounts of rain and ongoing water releases from Lake Eildon dam.

Support the local towns and make sure to set a watch zone for your location this long weekend and regularly check emergency radio broadcasters (ABC or UGFM radio) via your car radio if necessary.

What you should do:

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation. 
  • Farmers should move livestock and machinery to higher ground, if not already done and is safe to..
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations.
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • GMW Water are releasing water from Lake Eildon to control the rate the storage is filling and make room for further inflows.  
  • GMW advises It is important people who live or farm on floodplains have their properties prepared for any potential flood events. This includes ensuring there are no flaws with any dams on their properties and having a plan to move livestock and equipment to higher ground".
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
  • You may lose services including power, water, sewerage and telephone due to flooding.
  • Fishing, kayaking, Boating in floodwaters is dangerous due to debris, submerged trees and other hidden dangers.

This Flood Watch is being issued for South Gippsland Rivers.

WIDESPREAD RENEWED RIVER RISES AND MINOR FLOODING POSSIBLE FROM MONDAY AFTERNOON.

A deepening low will approach from the west, expected to be located near western Bass Strait by late Sunday, extending a cold front into western Victoria. The low will then dive south of Tasmania on Monday as the front crosses eastern Victoria, followed by another low pressure trough which will cross the state on Tuesday.

Widespread showers and storms are expected for Sunday, Monday and Tuesday

Catchments in the Flood Watch area are saturated, some of which are experiencing ongoing flooding due to recent rainfall.

Widespread renewed river level rises are likely and minor flooding may develop in the watch area from Monday afternoon. Catchments with recent or existing warnings where river levels are elevated may see fast response to further rainfall and moderate flooding is possible from early next week at some locations.

The Bureau of Meteorology is continuing to monitor the situation and will issue catchment specific warnings as required.

Catchment likely to be affected include:

South Gippsland Rivers
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Areas around rivers and streams may be flooded.
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 30/10/2022 03:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226

properties.name: Emergency Warning
properties.webBody:
This Emergency Warning is for Barmah and Lower Moira .
  • An evacuation warning remains current. It is still not safe to return. Continue to avoid flood-affected areas.
  • Dangerous floodwater and widespread and significantly contaminated floodwater remain in several parts of the town.

  • In flood-affected areas, there are now many cases of gastro (gastroenteritis, diarrhoea) causing people to get very sick.   
  • To prevent gastro always wash your hands after going to the toilet, before eating, preparing food, or cleaning your teeth etc. Only drink and wash, or wash clothes in known clean water.   
  • Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas.   

  • The Picola to Barmah Road is now open, however shallow water may still covers some parts of the road.
  • The Nathalia relief centre is still open at the Nathalia Community Centre,42 Robinson St, Nathalia.
It is not safe for people to return to Barmah and parts of Lower Moira.   
If you have not evacuated, you should now shelter in the highest location possible.
What you should do:

  • Be aware of the increased likelihood of trees falling due to the very wet ground, especially in windy conditions. Never shelter under trees.  

If you have not already evacuated:
  • Stay where you are and shelter in the highest location possible.
  • Be aware that you may be isolated by floodwater for a significant amount of time.
  • Check you have enough food, drinking water and medications - if you do not, phone Triple Zero (000) for assistance.
If you have already evacuated:
  • Do not return to your home until a Safe to Return notification is issued.
  • Register at a relief centre so that your friends, family and authorities can be informed that you are safe.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.

This evacuation warning will remain in place until the area is declared safe to return.
Impacts in your area:
  • Flood levels may remain above floor level of a single-storey home.
  • Based on historic data, this flood has had a similar impact as the 1993 flood.
  • Consequences of flooding along the Murray River will vary between NSW and Victoria. For more information relevant to your area, please check: www.ses.nsw.gov.au in NSW and www.emergency.vic.gov.au in Victor
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 31/10/2022 12:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:

  • Moderate flooding is occurring along the Campaspe River downstream of Rochester. 
  • The Campaspe River at Echuca is currently at 94.57 m AHD and steady, with moderate flooding. The river is expected to remain above the moderate flood level (94.40 m AHD) for the remainder of Saturday and into Sunday. 
  • River levels will remain elevated due to flood waters backing up from the Murray River and are expected to continue in the coming days.

The latest community newsletter from Saturday 29 October is available here: Community Newsletter
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater.
  
What you should do:

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.

  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.

  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations. 
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams. 
  • You may see animals attempting to move to higher ground, including snakes.
  • Leave all uninjured wildlife alone as they are likely to be fatigued and stressed.
  • If you see animals that appear injured or caught in flood water, call 136186 or via the Wildlife Emergency App.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 30/10/2022 11:00 am or as the situation changes.

Mosquito Alert     
With the recent floods in many areas across Victoria, the risk of mosquito breeding is high. Learn more about how to protect yourself and your family at https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/protect-yourself-mosquito-borne-disease.  
What you can do: 
  • Cover up - wear long, loose-fitting clothing.   
  • Use repellents that contain picaridin.  
  • Use mosquito nets or insect screens. 
  • Limit activity outdoors and move indoors if possible. 
Flood Recovery Hotline - Call 1800 560 760 
Flood Recovery Hotline is a single state-wide number, 1800 560 760, that Victorians impacted by the October 2022 floods can call for help or assistance with: 
  •  navigating available supports clean-up
  •  temporary accommodation 
  •  mental health and wellbeing support 
The recovery hotline is open from 7.30am-7.30pm everyday. 
Need an interpreter? Call the hotline on 1800 560 760 and press 9. 
For flood and storm information and support in NSW visit nsw.gov.au/floods   

If you require assistance relating to insurance matters, please call the Insurance Council Australia's disaster hotline on 1800 734 621.   

For local flood risk information: 
  • North Central CMA: nccma.vic.gov.au/floodplain-management 
  • VICSES Flood Guides: https://www.ses.vic.gov.au/plan-and-stay-safe/flood-guides/campaspe-shire-council 
  • Campaspe Shire Council: https://www.campaspe.vic.gov.au/Our-services/Emergency-management/Flood-event-2022

MODERATE FLOODING EXPECTED AT DOWNSTREAM LAKE EILDON SATURDAY MORNING
MODERATE FLOODING POSSIBLE AT SEYMOUR SUNDAY MORNING
MINOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT DOWNSTREAM LAKE EILDON, TAGGERTY, SEYMOUR, MURCHISON, SHEPPARTON AND MCCOYS BRIDGE

Moderate flooding is expected at Downstream Lake Eildon during Saturday morning and may develop along the Goulburn River at Seymour during Sunday morning. 
Minor flooding is currently occurring along the Goulburn River catchment at Downstream Lake Eildon, Taggerty, Seymour, Murchison, Shepparton and McCoys Bridge.
Goulburn Murray Water has advised that releases from Lake Eildon will be increasing from the current 24,000 ML/d up to around 30,000 ML/d by Saturday late morning.
The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.

Yea River:
River levels along the Yea River are below the minor flood level and falling.

Updated Community information:
In flood-affected areas, there are now many cases of gastro (gastroenteritis, diarrhoea) causing people to get very sick.  
To prevent gastro always wash your hands after going to the toilet, before eating, preparing food, or cleaning your teeth etc. Only drink and wash, or wash clothes in known clean water.
Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas. 
The wet ground conditions have resulted in many trees falling without warning.  If it gets windy, trees will become more unstable and deadly.  Never park, take shelter or camp under a tree.

If you are planning to camp close to rivers or creeks DONT! 

Unexpected river rises are very likely after even small amounts of rainfall and ongoing water releases from Lake Eildon.

Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert. Never enter floodwater.

In the VicEmergency App, add a watch zone for your campsite and regularly check emergency broadcasters via car radio if necessary.
What you should do:
  • Review your emergency plan and check your emergency kit is fully stocked, if you have one. 
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • If cleaning after damage has occurred, protect your health and safety. 
  • Protect your lungs by wearing a N95 or P2 mask. Wear strong boots, gloves and protective clothing and wash your hands and clothes regularly. 
  • Stagnant water can be harmful to your health. 
  • Dont swim, drink or wash in stagnant water. Smelly black water can be reported to EPA on 1800 560 760
Impacts in your area: 
  • Local roads may be closed and low bridges may be underwater.
  • Areas around rivers and streams may be flooded.
  • Low lying caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.

The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.
Recovery: 
Flood Recovery Hotline is a single state-wide number, 1800 560 760, that Victorians impacted by the October 2022 floods can call for help or assistance with: 
  • Register for clean up on private property; 
  • Navigating financial and other support 
  • Access to temporary accommodation 
  • Mental health and wellbeing support 
The recovery hotline is open from 7:30am-7:30pm everyday.   Call 1800 560 760 or visit Emergency Recovery Vic for further information. 

For life-threatening emergencies, call Triple Zero (000) immediately. For emergency assistance during floods call 132 500 for SES assistance.

Health Messaging 
  • Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. 
  • Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas. 
  • Stay out of the water - skin contact with floodwater or mud can cause illness and skin infections. Cover cuts and if you are injured during your clean up; clean the wound and contact your doctor immediately.  
  • Private water supplies may also be contaminated from floodwater, debris and chemicals. If your water supply tastes, looks or smells unusual, do not use it for drinking, preparing food, and do not give it to animals.  
  • Medicines, stored at home and affected by flood water may now be unsafe and extreme caution should be taken in trying to salvage any medicines. 
  • Mosquitoes can also breed rapidly in stagnant waters. Drain any water from containers such as plant pots, tyres, buckets, and roof gutters to control mosquitos around your home. 
  • Flooding can also cause excessive mould growth which must be cleaned up before moving back to your home as it can make you sick. 
  • Any damaged gas or electricity supplies need to be declared safe by a qualified electrician or plumber. 
  • Do not use a portable generator indoors, they can produce carbon monoxide gas which could build up in a confined space and make you sick or be fatal. 
  • Food safety should also be considered and ALL food that has been flood damaged should be thrown away, including canned and packaged foods. 
  • It is important to look after your mental health and that of friends, family and neighbours. If at any time you are worried about your mental health or the mental health of a loved one, call Lifeline 13 11 14 or the Suicide Call Back Service on 1300 659 467.
Register Find Unite - Red Cross 
Red Cross has opened Register.Find.Reunite. and is urging people affected by the Victorian Floods to get in touch with their families and friends. Register.Find.Reunite. helps find and reunite family, friends and loved ones during a disaster. People can register on the Red Cross website at register.redcross.org.au, or by phone at 1800 727 077.

This Flood Watch is being issued for Yea River.


MODERATE FLOODING EXPECTED AT DOWNSTREAM LAKE EILDON SATURDAY MORNING
MODERATE FLOODING POSSIBLE AT SEYMOUR SUNDAY MORNING
MINOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT DOWNSTREAM LAKE EILDON, TAGGERTY, SEYMOUR, MURCHISON, SHEPPARTON AND MCCOYS BRIDGE 

Moderate flooding is expected at Downstream Lake Eildon during Saturday morning and may develop along the Goulburn River at Seymour during Sunday morning. 
Minor flooding is currently occurring along the Goulburn River catchment at Downstream Lake Eildon, Taggerty, Seymour, Murchison, Shepparton and McCoys Bridge.
Goulburn Murray Water has advised that releases from Lake Eildon will be increasing from the current 24,000 ML/d up to around 30,000 ML/d by Saturday late morning.
The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary. 

Yea River:
River levels along the Yea River are below the minor flood level and falling. 

Updated Community information:
In flood-affected areas, there are now many cases of gastro (gastroenteritis, diarrhoea) causing people to get very sick.  
To prevent gastro always wash your hands after going to the toilet, before eating, preparing food, or cleaning your teeth etc. Only drink and wash, or wash clothes in known clean water.
Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas.  


The wet ground conditions have resulted in many trees falling without warning.  If it gets windy, trees will become more unstable and deadly.  Never park, take shelter or camp under a tree. 

If you are planning to camp close to rivers or creeks DONT! 

Unexpected river rises are very likely after even small amounts of rainfall and ongoing water releases from Lake Eildon.

Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert. Never enter floodwater.

In the VicEmergency App, add a watch zone for your campsite and regularly check emergency broadcasters via car radio if necessary.

properties.name: Advice
properties.webBody:
This Flood Watch is being issued for Tanjiil River.

WIDESPREAD RENEWED RIVER RISES AND MINOR FLOODING POSSIBLE FROM MONDAY AFTERNOON.

A deepening low will approach from the west, expected to be located near western Bass Strait by late Sunday, extending a cold front into western Victoria. The low will then dive south of Tasmania on Monday as the front crosses eastern Victoria, followed by another low pressure trough which will cross the state on Tuesday.

Widespread showers and storms are expected for Sunday, Monday and Tuesday.

Catchments in the Flood Watch area are saturated, some of which are experiencing ongoing flooding due to recent rainfall.

Widespread renewed river level rises are likely and minor flooding may develop in the watch area from Monday afternoon. Catchments with recent or existing warnings where river levels are elevated may see fast response to further rainfall and moderate flooding is possible from early next week at some locations.

Catchment likely to be affected include:

Latrobe River
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Areas around rivers and streams may be flooded.
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 30/10/2022 03:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226

This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for the Dandenong Creek.

The Dandenong Creek catchment has recorded rainfall averaging about 30 mm since 09:00 AM Thursday 27 October 2022. 
Rainfall totals of 5-15 mm are forecast for the catchment Friday 28 October 2022.
Water levels of the Dandenong Creek at various locations are rising in response to the rain.
The level of the Dandenong Creek at Rowville (Police Road RB) is currently at 4.29 metres, and steady. 
The river level peaked at 4.44 metres at 6.00 AM Friday morning 28 October 2022. 
If the rainfall occurs as forecast it is expected to peak again around the Minor Flood Level (4.60 metres) on Saturday morning 29 October 2022.
Minor flooding in the Dandenong Creek catchment is affecting low-lying areas adjacent to the waterway
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.

properties.name: Watch & Act
properties.webBody:
This Major Flood Warning is being issued for Wharparilla.

Flooding has impacted residents in the area of O'Dwyer Road, Wharparilla. 

Flooding is expected to remain at current levels for the next week.

The latest Community Newsletter from Saturday 29 October is available here: Community Newsletter
Move to higher ground. Act now - immediately take actions to protect your life and property.
What you should do: 

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater. 
  • Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary. 

If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around and find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges. 
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow. 
Stay informed - listen to emergency broadcasters and monitor warnings.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in many locations.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service. 

The next update is expected by 30/10/2022 10:00 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226 
  • VicEmergency app 
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods) 
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV. 

Accessibility:

properties.name: Watch & Act
properties.location: Yarra River from Millgrove to Coldstream
properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for the Yarra River from Millgrove to Coldstream.

The Yarra River catchment has recorded rainfall averaging about 17 mm in the upper part of the catchment and about 7 mm in the lower part of the catchment since 09:00 AM Friday 28 October 2022. Rainfall totals of 5-10 mm are forecast for the catchment for Saturday 29 October 2022.

Yarra River from Millgrove to Coldstream:

The level of the Yarra River at Coldstream is currently at 5.83 metres, exceeding the Moderate Flood Level (5.10 metres)and steady. It peaked at 5.85 metres at 2 AM Saturday morning and is expected to remain above the Moderate Flood Level (5.10 metres) until Sunday 30 October 2022.
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater. 
What you should do:

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations.
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
  • Main roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding.
  • Parks, hiking tracks and campgrounds are closed due to flooding. To find out more go to www.parkweb.vic.gov.au/safety/flood-affected-parks.

Areas at risk in the event of flooding in Yarra Junction include:
  • Doon Reserve Caravan Park
  • Doon Road
  • Lowes Road
  • Settlement Road
  • Corduroy Road
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 29/10/2022 09:30 pm or as the situation changes.

properties.location: Murray River downstream of Hume Dam to Tocumwal
properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Murray River downstream of Hume Dam to Tocumwal.

This is an update, replacing the Advice message issued at 4.33 PM 27/10/2022.

Flood operations are being conducted by the Murray-Darling Basin Authority (MDBA) at Hume Dam to manage inflows from the upper Murray, Mitta Mitta River and other tributaries. MDBA are working closely with the Bureau and Water NSW to plan release strategies.

Further rainfall is forecast for the reminder of Friday across parts of the Murray River Basin and another trough may bring showers and thunderstorm during Monday and Tuesday, which may cause renewed river level rises and flooding. 

The situation is being closely monitored and revised predictions will be provided if necessary.

Murray River downstream of Hume Dam to Tocumwal:
Minor flooding is occurring along the Murray River at Albury and possible at Tocumwal. Moderate flooding is occurring at Corowa.

The Murray River at Albury is currently at 4.36 metres and steady, with minor flooding.  The Murray River at Corowa is currently at 6.09 metres and falling, with moderate flooding.

Renewed minor flooding is possible along the Murray River at Tocumwal where the river level may reach the minor flood level (6.40 metres) overnight Friday into Saturday. Further rises are possible.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.

Be aware of the increased likelihood of trees falling due to the very wet ground, especially in windy conditions. Never shelter under trees. 
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
  • Consequences of flooding along the Murray River will vary between NSW and Victoria. For more information relevant to your area, please check: www.ses.nsw.gov.au in NSW and www.emergency.vic.gov.au in Victoria.


Impacts in your area: 

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • For more information on road closures check the VicRoads website traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au.
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.

This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 29/10/2022 05:30 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
  • For road closure information go to www.traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au or phone 13 11 70.
  • For health information and support contact the below organisations: Lifeline on www.lifeline.org.au or phone 13 11 14. Beyond Blue on www.beyondblue.org.au or phone 1300 224 636. Kids Helpine on www.kidshelp.com.au or phone 1800 551 800. SANE Australia on www.sane.org or phone 1800 187 263.
Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline. 
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.  

Health Messaging 
  • Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. 
  • Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home. Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas. 
  •  Stay out of the water - skin contact with floodwater or mud can cause illness and skin infections. Cover cuts and if you are injured during your clean up; clean the wound and contact your doctor immediately.  
  •  Private water supplies may also be contaminated from floodwater, debris and chemicals. If your water supply tastes, looks or smells unusual, do not use it for drinking, preparing food, and do not give it to animals.  
  •  Medicines, stored at home and affected by flood water may now be unsafe and extreme caution should be taken in trying to salvage any medicines. 
  • Mosquitoes can also breed rapidly in stagnant waters. Drain any water from containers such as plant pots, tyres, buckets, and roof gutters to control mosquitos around your home. 
  •  Flooding can also cause excessive mould growth which must be cleaned up before moving back to your home as it can make you sick.
  • Any damaged gas or electricity supplies need to be declared safe by a qualified electrician or plumber. Do not use a portable generator indoors, they can produce carbon monoxide gas which could build up in a confined space and make you sick or be fatal.
  • Food safety should also be considered and ALL food that has been flood damaged should be thrown away - including canned and packaged foods. 
  • It is important to look after your mental health and that of friends, family and neighbours. If at any time you are worried about your mental health or the mental health of a loved one, call Lifeline 13 11 14 or the Suicide Call Back Service on 1300 659 467.
Recovery:
Flood Recovery Hotline is a single state-wide number, 1800 560 760, that Victorians impacted by the October 2022 floods can call for help or assistance with: 
  • Register for clean up on private property; 
  • Navigating financial and other support;
  • Access to temporary accommodation;
  • Mental health and wellbeing support.

The recovery hotline is open from 7:30am-7:30pm everyday.   Call 1800 560 760 or visit www.erv.vic.gov.au for further information. 

For life-threatening emergencies, call Triple Zero (000) immediately. 
For emergency assistance during floods call 132 500 for SES assistance.

Register Find Unite - Red Cross 
Red Cross has opened Register.Find.Reunite. and is urging people affected by the Victorian Floods to get in touch with their families and friends. Register.Find.Reunite. helps find and reunite family, friends and loved ones during a disaster. People can register on the Red Cross website at register.redcross.org.au, or by phone at 1800 727 077. 

This is a community message to advise the community not to build own levees as it changes the flow of the water and impacting other properties.

properties.webBody:
This Major Flood Warning is being issued for Murray River downstream of Tocumwal to Barham. 

Murray River downstream of Tocumwal to Barham:

  • Major flooding is occurring at Echuca, Moama, Torrumbarry and Barham.
  • The Murray River at Echuca peaked at 94.98 metres AHD around 11:45 pm Wednesday and is currently at 94.95 metres AHD and falling slowly, with major flooding.
  • The Murray River at Echuca may remain above the major flood level (94.40 metres AHD) until 05-06 November.
  • The Murray River at Torrumbarry Weir may peak around 7.85 metres over the weekend, with major flooding.
  • The Murray River at Barham is currently at 6.20 metres and falling slowly, with major flooding. 
  • The Murray River at Barham may remain above the major flood level (6.10 metres) until 10-12 November.
Torrumbarry to Leitchville
  • A Watch and Act - Move to Higher Ground message is in place for Torrumbarry, Patho, Gunbower and Leitchville. 
  • Ongoing maintenance works are continuing to improve the serviceability of the levee with continual monitoring occurring. 
Wharparilla
  • Watch and Act - Move to Higher Ground messages are in place for O'Dwyer Road and Wharparilla-Glyn Road.
There are Evacuation Warnings in place for 
  • Echuca and Echuca Village, and 
  • Barmah and Lower Moira. 
Move to higher ground. Act now - immediately take actions to protect your life and property.
What you should do: 
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater. 
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater. 
  • Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary.
  • For commercial and recreational users of the Murray River: NSW State Emergency Services have declared an emergency area on the Murray River for areas downstream of Tocumal Road Bridge to Barham Bridge under the state Emergency Services Act 1989 (NSW) (SES Act). Do not enter the emergency area. This applies to all commercial and recreational users. Visit the NSW SES website for information: https://www.ses.nsw.gov.au/news/all-news/2022/emergency-area-declared-murray-river/
  • Consequences of flooding along the Murray River will vary between NSW and Victoria. For more information relevant to your area, please check: www.ses.nsw.gov.au in NSW and www.emergency.vic.gov.au in Victoria.
If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around and find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.   
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow. 
  • Stay informed - listen to emergency broadcasters and monitor warnings.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in many locations. 
  • Main roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding.
  • You may see animals attempting to move to higher ground, including snakes.
  • Leave all uninjured wildlife alone as they are likely to be fatigued and stressed.
  • If you see animals that appear injured or caught in flood water, call 136186 or via the Wildlife Emergency App
This message was issued by State Emergency Service. 

The next update is expected by 29/10/2022 05:30 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226 
  • VicEmergency app

  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Murray River downstream of Tocumwal to Barham:

- Major flooding is occurring at Echuca, Moama, Torrumbarry and Barham.
- The Murray River at Echuca peaked at 94.98 metres AHD around 11:45 pm Wednesday and is currently at 94.95 metres AHD and falling slowly, with major flooding.
- The Murray River at Echuca may remain above the major flood level (94.40 metres AHD) until 05-06 November.
- The Murray River at Torrumbarry Weir may peak around 7.85 metres over the weekend, with major flooding.
- The Murray River at Barham is currently at 6.20 metres and falling slowly, with major flooding. 
- The Murray River at Barham may remain above the major flood level (6.10 metres) until 10-12 November. 

Torrumbarry to Leitchville
- A Watch and Act - Move to Higher Ground message is in place for Torrumbarry, Patho, Gunbower and Leitchville. 
- Ongoing maintenance works are continuing to improve the serviceability of the levee with continual monitoring occurring. 

Wharparilla
- Watch and Act - Move to Higher Ground messages are in place for O'Dwyer Road and Wharparilla-Glyn Road.

There are Evacuation Warnings in place for 
- Echuca and Echuca Village, and 
- Barmah and Lower Moira. 


Move to higher ground. Act now - immediately take actions to protect your life and property.

This Flood Watch is being issued for Loddon River upstream of Laanecoorie.

  • River levels are currently elevated along the Loddon River upstream of Laanecoorie at Newstead, and along the Bet Bet Creek at Bet Bet. The Loddon River Downstream (D/S) Cairn Curran is currently at 1.85 metres and steady, below the minor flood level. 
  • The Loddon River Downstream (D/S) Cairn Curran is likely to remain just below the minor flood level (2.00 m) for the remainder of Saturday and into Sunday.
The latest community newsletter from Saturday 29 October is available here: Community Newsletter
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. 
  • Check the VicRoads website traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au for information on road closures.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
  • Be aware of the risk of mosquitos bring and cover up with long, loose-fitting clothing.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Areas around rivers and streams may be flooded.
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 30/10/2022 01:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Mosquito Alert: 
With the recent floods in many areas across Victoria, the risk of mosquito breeding is high. Learn more about how to protect yourself and your family at https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/protect-yourself-mosquito-borne-disease.

What you can do:
  • Cover up - wear long, loose-fitting clothing 
  • Use repellents that contain picaridin or DEET 
  • Use mosquito nets or insect screens.
  • Limit activity outdoors and move indoors if possible. 

Flood Recovery Hotline - Call 1800 560 760
Flood Recovery Hotline is a single state-wide number, 1800 560 760, that Victorians impacted by the October 2022 floods can call for help or assistance with:
  • navigating available supports
  • clean-up
  • temporary accommodation
  • mental health and wellbeing support
The recovery hotline is open from 7.30am-7.30pm everyday.

Need an interpreter? Call the hotline on 1800 560 760 and press 9.
For flood and storm information and support in NSW visit nsw.gov.au/floods
If you require assistance relating to insurance matters, please call the Insurance Council Australia's disaster hotline on 1800 734 621.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for the Goulburn River upstream of Lake Eildon at Doherty's

MINOR FLOODING CURRENTLY OCCURRING upstream and downstream of LAKE EILDON, including at TAGGERTY, SEYMOUR, MURCHISON, SHEPPARTON AND MCCOYS BRIDGE  
 
MODERATE FLOODING EXPECTED AT DOWNSTREAM of LAKE EILDON SATURDAY MORNING  
MODERATE FLOODING POSSIBLE AT SEYMOUR SUNDAY MORNING      

Goulburn River upstream of Lake Eildon:  
  • Minor flooding is occurring along the Goulburn River upstream of Lake Eildon at Dohertys, where the river level is at 2.32 metres and rising slowly.  
  • River levels along the Delatite River at Tonga Bridge are below the minor flood level and falling.  

Goulburn River downstream of Lake Eildon to Seymour  
  • Moderate flooding is expected at Downstream of Lake Eildon during Saturday morning and may develop along the Goulburn River at Seymour during Sunday morning.   
  • Minor flooding is currently occurring along the Goulburn River catchment at Downstream of Lake Eildon, Taggerty, Seymour, Murchison, Shepparton and McCoys Bridge.  
  •  Goulburn Murray Water has advised that releases from Lake Eildon will be increasing from the current 24,000 ML/d up to around 30,000 ML/d by Saturday late morning.  
  •  The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.   
  •  Moderate flooding may occur along the Goulburn River Lake Eildon to Seymour
  •  Minor flooding is currently occurring at Trawool. 
  • River levels are rising and are expected to remain above the minor flood level during Saturday and into Sunday.  
  • The Goulburn River downstream of Lake Eildon is currently at 3.81 metres and steady, with minor flooding.  
  • The Goulburn River downstream of Lake Eildon is expected to exceed the moderate flood level (4.00 m) Saturday morning.  
  • The river level is likely to reach around 4.40 metres late Saturday morning.  
  • The Goulburn River at Seymour  is currently at 4.56 metres and steady, with minor flooding.  The Goulburn River at Seymour may reach the moderate flood level (5.20 m) Sunday morning. 
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.

If you are planning to camp or go bush driving close to rivers or creeks this long weekend, DON'T!

Unexpected and rapid river and creek level rises are very likely even with small amounts of rain and ongoing water releases from Lake Eildon dam.

Support the local towns and make sure to set a watch zone for your location this long weekend and regularly check emergency radio broadcasters (ABC or UGFM radio) via your car radio if necessary.
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. 
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground if not already done.
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.
  • Don't go fishing, kayaking, or boating. Floodwaters is dangerous due to debris, submerged trees and other hidden dangers. 
Impacts in your area: 

  • Wet ground conditions have resulted in many trees falling without notice or. If it gets windy, trees will become more unstable and deadly. Never park, shelter or set up camp under trees.
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
  • If you are planning to camp or go bush driving close to rivers or creeks this long weekend, DON'T!   Unexpected and rapid river and creek levels are very likely even with small amounts of rain.   
  • Support the local towns and make sure to set a watch zone for your location this long weekend and regularly check emergency radio broadcasters (ABC or UGFM radio) via your car radio if necessary.
  • Don't go fishing, kayaking, or boating. Floodwater is dangerous due to debris, submerged trees and other hidden dangers. 
  • Parks, hiking tracks and campgrounds may be closed due to flooding. To find out more go to www.parkweb.vic.gov.au/safety/flood-affected-parks.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 29/10/2022 06:30 pm or as the situation changes.

This Flood Watch is being issued for Bemm, Cann and Genoa Rivers.

WIDESPREAD RENEWED RIVER RISES AND MINOR FLOODING POSSIBLE FROM MONDAY AFTERNOON.

A deepening low will approach from the west on Sunday, expected to be located near western Bass Strait by evening with a cold front extending into western Victoria. The low will then dive south of Tasmania on Monday as the front moves over eastern Victoria, followed by another low pressure trough which will cross the state on Tuesday.

Widespread showers and storms are expected for Sunday, Monday and Tuesday.

Catchments in the Flood Watch area are saturated, some of which are experiencing ongoing flooding due to recent rainfall.

Catchments likely to be affected include:

Bemm, Cann and Genoa Rivers
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Areas around rivers and streams may be flooded.
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 30/10/2022 03:00 pm or as the situation changes.

properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Yarra River from Warrandyte to Abbotsford.

The Yarra River catchment has recorded rainfall averaging about 17 mm in the upper part of the catchment and about 7 mm in the lower part of the catchment since 09:00 AM Friday 28 October 2022. Rainfall totals of 5-10 mm are forecast for the catchment for Saturday 29 October 2022.

Yarra River from Warrandyte to Abbotsford:

The level of the Yarra River at Templestowe is currently at 4.45 metres, exceeding the Minor Flood Level (3.50 metres) and rising. It peaked at 5.0 metres at 5 AM Friday 28 October and is expected to peak again below the Moderate Flood Level (6.00 metres) on Saturday 29 October 2022.

The level of the Yarra River at Heidelberg is currently at 7.82 metres, exceeding the Minor Flood Level (6.00 metres) and rising. It peaked at 8.1 metres at 11 AM Friday 28 October and is expected to peak again around the Moderate Flood Level (8.30 metres) on Saturday 29 October 2022.

The level of the Yarra River at Alphington is currently at 4.35 metres, exceeding the Minor Flood Level (3.00 metres) and steady. It is expected to peak below the Moderate Flood Level (6.00 metres) on Saturday evening 29 October 2022.

The level of the Yarra River at Abbotsford is currently at 4.44 metres, exceeding the Minor Flood Level (2.70 metres) and steady. It is expected to peak above the Minor Flood Level (2.70 metres) on Saturday 29 October 2022.

Minor to Moderate flooding in the Yarra/Watts River catchments are causing substantial inundation in rural and/or urban areas, and disruption to traffic. Melba Highway at Yarra Glen is expected to get flooded.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.
Impacts in your area: 

  • Minor flooding in the Yarra River catchment is affecting low-lying areas adjacent to the waterway including bicycle paths.
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • For more information on road closures check the VicRoads website traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 29/10/2022 09:30 pm or as the situation changes.

This Flood Watch is being issued for Castle Creek.

MODERATE FLOODING CONTINUING AT KIALLA WEST DURING SATURDAY AND INTO SUNDAY
MINOR FLOODING EASING AT EUROA

Rainfall during Friday caused small renewed rises along the Seven Creeks, with minor flooding currently easing at Euroa. Moderate flooding is continuing at Kialla West.
Further rainfall is forecast for the Seven and Castle Creek catchments from Sunday evening which may result in renewed river level rises into next week. The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.

Castle Creek:
River levels are easing along the Castle Creek and expected to remain below the minor flood level at Telfords Bridge over the remainder of the weekend.

Updated Community information:
In flood-affected areas, there are now many cases of gastro (gastroenteritis, diarrhoea) causing people to get very sick.   

To prevent gastro always wash your hands after going to the toilet, before eating, preparing food, or cleaning your teeth etc. Only drink and wash, or wash clothes in known clean water.   

Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas. 
The wet ground conditions have resulted in many trees falling without warning.  If it gets windy, trees will become more unstable and deadly.  Never park, take shelter or camp under a tree.   

If you are planning to camp close to rivers or creeks DONT!    

Unexpected river rises are very likely after even small amounts of rainfall.

Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert. Never enter floodwater.   

In the VicEmergency App, add a watch zone for your campsite and regularly check emergency broadcasters via car radio if necessary.
What you should do:
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Areas around rivers and streams may be flooded.
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
  • Local roads may be closed and low bridges may be underwater.
  • For more information on road closures go to traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 30/10/2022 12:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.
Recovery: 
Flood Recovery Hotline is a single state-wide number, 1800 560 760, that Victorians impacted by the October 2022 floods can call for help or assistance with: 
  • Register for clean up on private property; 
  • Navigating financial and other support 
  • Access to temporary accommodation 
  • Mental health and wellbeing support 

The recovery hotline is open from 7:30am-7:30pm everyday.   Call 1800 560 760 or visit www.erv.vic.gov.au for further information. 

For life-threatening emergencies, call Triple Zero (000) immediately. 
For emergency assistance during floods call 132 500 for SES assistance.

Health Messaging 
  • Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. 
  • Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas. 
  • Stay out of the water - skin contact with floodwater or mud can cause illness and skin infections. Cover cuts and if you are injured during your clean up; clean the wound and contact your doctor immediately.  
  • Private water supplies may also be contaminated from floodwater, debris and chemicals. If your water supply tastes, looks or smells unusual, do not use it for drinking, preparing food, and do not give it to animals.  
  • Medicines, stored at home and affected by flood water may now be unsafe and extreme caution should be taken in trying to salvage any medicines. 
  • Mosquitoes can also breed rapidly in stagnant waters. Drain any water from containers such as plant pots, tyres, buckets, and roof gutters to control mosquitos around your home. 
  • Flooding can also cause excessive mould growth which must be cleaned up before moving back to your home as it can make you sick. 
  • Any damaged gas or electricity supplies need to be declared safe by a qualified electrician or plumber. 
  • Do not use a portable generator indoors, they can produce carbon monoxide gas which could build up in a confined space and make you sick or be fatal. 
  • Food safety should also be considered and ALL food that has been flood damaged should be thrown away, including canned and packaged foods. 
  • It is important to look after your mental health and that of friends, family and neighbours. If at any time you are worried about your mental health or the mental health of a loved one, call Lifeline 13 11 14 or the Suicide Call Back Service on 1300 659 467.

Register Find Unite - Red Cross 
Red Cross has opened Register.Find.Reunite. and is urging people affected by the Victorian Floods to get in touch with their families and friends. Register.Find.Reunite. helps find and reunite family, friends and loved ones during a disaster. People can register on the Red Cross website at register.redcross.org.au, or by phone at 1800 727 077.

properties.webBody:
This Warning is being issued for Bogong Village and Falls Creek

  • A Landslide has occurred on the Bogong High Plains Road at Bogong Village.
  • There is a large, active, slow moving landslide on the Bogong High Plains Road in the area near Spring Saddle Track above Bogong Village.
  • After recent heavy rainfall, cracking has been identified in the area around Spring Saddle Track and debris has been moving from below the track onto the Bogong High Plains Road.
  • Further rainfall and snow are forecast which could result in imminent failure and pose a threat to life and property. 

  • The Bogong-High Plains Road is closed from Mount Beauty to all traffic - until further notice, and will not reopen until deemed safe.

  • An Exclusion Zone has been established, prohibiting entry into the area defined in the map which is available at https://bit.ly/3gOXZb7. Access to this area is strictly prohibited and is a threat to life if you enter.

This is an update, replacing the warning issued at 2:54 PM, Friday 28/10/2022.
Avoid the area. Stay clear of fallen earth and trees and blocked or damaged roads. Be aware of other hazards caused by the landslide. Do not enter the exclusion zone.

Visitors are advised not to travel to Falls Creek over the Melbourne Cup weekend due to forecast severe weather and snow conditions.
What you should do:
  • If you have chosen to remain, please monitor the road conditions. 
  • If another landslide occurs, act quickly.
  • If you are outside when a landslide occurs, move quickly and keep clear of embankments, trees, power lines and poles.
  • If you are inside, move to the part of building that is furthest away from the approaching landslide and take shelter under a table or bench.
  • Stay away from the impacted area to allow emergency services to help affected communities.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters  and monitoring warnings.

Travelling:
  • Plan your trip in advance - travel may take longer due to closed roads and poor driving conditions.
  • Visitors are advised not to travel to Falls Creek over the Melbourne Cup weekend due to forecast severe weather and snow conditions.
  • There will be no public access to Falls Creek and Bogong Village as the Bogong High Plains Road will remain closed until deemed safe.
  • The Bogong High Plains Road, south of Falls Creek is open to local traffic only, accessible via the Omeo Highway.
Impacts in your area:
The landslide has resulted in:
  • Fallen trees and branches.
  • Dangerous road conditions.
  • Mud and debris on the road.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 31/10/2022 10:00 am or as the situation changes.

properties.text: WARNING - LANDSLIDE Incident Location: Bogong Village and Falls Creek Issue Date: Friday 28 October 2022, 05:03 pm Next Update: Monday 31 October 2022, 10:00 am More details at http://emergency.vic.gov.au/respond/#!/warning/25305/moreinfo This Warning is being issued for Bogong Village and Falls Creek - A Landslide has occurred on the Bogong High Plains Road at Bogong Village. - There is a large, active, slow moving landslide on the Bogong High Plains Road in the area near Spring Saddle Track above Bogong Village. - After recent heavy rainfall, cracking has been identified in the area around Spring Saddle Track and debris has been moving from below the track onto the Bogong High Plains Road. - Further rainfall and snow are forecast which could result in imminent failure and pose a threat to life and property. - The Bogong-High Plains Road is closed from Mount Beauty to all traffic - until further notice, and will not reopen until deemed safe. - An Exclusion Zone has been established, prohibiting entry into the area defined in the map which is available at https://bit.ly/3gOXZb7. Access to this area is strictly prohibited and is a threat to life if you enter. This is an update, replacing the warning issued at 2:54 PM, Friday 28/10/2022. Avoid the area. Stay clear of fallen earth and trees and blocked or damaged roads. Be aware of other hazards caused by the landslide. Do not enter the exclusion zone. Visitors are advised not to travel to Falls Creek over the Melbourne Cup weekend due to forecast severe weather and snow conditions.

properties.name: Emergency Warning
properties.webBody:
This updated Emergency Warning is being issued for Kerang.

  • An evacuation warning remains current and it is still not safe to return.
  • The Loddon River at MV Hwy Bridge is currently at 77.55m Australian Height Datum (AHD) and falling slowly, with moderate flooding. The Loddon River at MV Hwy Bridge is likely to remain around the moderate flood level (77.50m AHD) overnight Friday into Saturday.
  • Dangerous flood water is still significantly impacting Kerang and surrounding areas, continue to avoid flood-affected areas.
  • Emergency services and Gannawarra Shire Council are working together to assess levee integrity, road safety and identify any impacts to essential services.
  • Although the river has peaked, with some levees still overtopped in sections, many areas are still experiencing significant flooding and emergency services continue efforts towards sandbagging and asset protection.
It is not safe for people to return to Kerang. If you have not evacuated, avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater.
If you have not already evacuated:
  • Stay where you are and be aware of changing conditions. If floodwater comes inside, move to a higher point such as a kitchen bench or second story.
  • Be aware that you may still become isolated by floodwater for a significant amount of time.
  • Check you have enough food, drinking water and medications - if you do not, phone Triple Zero (000) for assistance.
If you have already evacuated:
  • Do not return to your home until a Safe to Return notification is issued.
  • Register at a relief centre so that your friends, family and authorities can be informed that you are safe.
  • Stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
This evacuation warning will remain in place until emergency services have confirmed that the threat to Kerang has reduced, and it is safe to return.
Impacts in your area:
  • The Benjeroop-Lake Charm Road is closed
  • The Kerang-Quambatook Road is closed.
  • The Murray Valley Highway is closed east of Kerang between Sleepy Lane and Phillips Road.
  • The Old Echuca Road is closed between Durham Ox and Kerang.
  • The Murray Valley Highway is closed between Kerang and Benjeroop-Lake Charm Road.
  • For the most current information go to: https://traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au/
  • Be aware that snakes may look for shelter and food inside houses, storage sheds and other buildings near floodwater. Damaged structures and debris are more accessible to snakes.
Mosquito alert:
The risk of mosquito breeding is high. You can reduce your risk of being bitten and getting sick:
  • Cover up - wear long, loose-fitting clothing
  • Use repellents that contain picaridin or DEET
  • Use mosquito nets or insect screens
  • Limit activity outdoors and move indoors if possible.
Learn more about how to protect yourself and your family at https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/protect-yourself-mosquito-borne-disease
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 29/10/2022 12:00 pm or as the situation changes.
