properties.webBody:
This Major Flood Warning is being issued for Gunbower, Leitchville, Torrumbarry and Patho. 

  • The Murray River at Torrumbarry Weir may peak around 7.85 metres over the weekend, with major flooding.
  • The Torrumbarry Weir water level was 7.83 as at 12:00pm on Friday 28 October.
  • Ongoing maintenance works are continuing to improve the serviceability of the levee with continual monitoring occurring.
Move to higher ground. Act now - immediately take actions to protect your life and property.
What you should do: 

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater. 
  • Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary. 

If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Turn off the gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around and find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges. 

If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow. 
  • Lift it. Be prepared to move valuables and household items to higher ground, on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds. 

Stay informed - listen to emergency broadcasters and monitor warnings.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in many locations. 
  • Main roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding.
  • You may see animals attempting to move to higher ground, including snakes. Leave all uninjured wildlife alone and they are likely to be fatigued and stressed. If you see animals that appear to e injured or caught in floodwater, call 136 186 or advise via the wildlife emergency app.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service. 

The next update is expected by 29/10/2022 05:30 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226

This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for the Ovens River downstream of Rocky Point.

Moderate Flooding is likely at Wangaratta from Saturday Afternoon.

Minor flooding is currently occurring along the Ovens River at Wangaratta. Further rises are expected where moderate flooding is likely to develop from Saturday afternoon as upstream floodwaters arrive.

In the 24 hours to 9:00 am Saturday rainfall totals of up to 25 mm have been observed across the Ovens and King River catchment. No significant rainfall is forecast for the remainder of Saturday.

Ovens River downstream of Rocky Point
  • The Ovens River at Wangaratta is currently at 12.01 metres and rising, with minor flooding. It is likely to exceed the moderate flood level (12.40 m) Saturday afternoon. The river level may peak near 12.50 metres overnight Saturday into Sunday.
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater. 
What you should do:
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • If you are camping close to a creek or river, you may be at risk of flooding and need to move to higher ground, away from waterways.
  • Follow your emergency plan and locate your emergency kit, if you have one.
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • A number of local roads and may be closed due to flooding.
At the Minor Flood Level (11.9m):
  • Water up to Yogi's chin in Apex Park
  • Apex Park and farmland along the Ovens, King and possibly the Fifteen Mile Creek floodplains north, south and east of Wangaratta may begin flooding
  • Bike paths and walking tracks around and downstream of Apex Park and the Northern Beaches may be closed
  • Many riverside carparks may be closed including Sydney Beach, Bickerton St and Baker St
  • The Great Alpine Road at East Wangaratta is closed due to flooding, with detours in place

At the Moderate Flood Level (12.4m):
  • Extensive flooding through APEX Park, water up to Yogi's mouth
  • Bickerton St carpark will be closed and the access road to Painters Island Caravan Park flooded
  • Shallow flooding to Pinkerton Cres and backyards along Templeton St and Baker St

The following roads may be affected by flooding as the river level rises and may be closed:
  • The Great Alpine Road, East Wangaratta
  • Peechelba Road (East of the Ovens River)
  • Wilson Road (outside of the levee protected area)
  • Markwood-Everton Road
  • Bickerton Street, including the car parking areas
  • Milawa-Tarrawingee Road
  • College Street, preventing access to the Northern Beaches carpark
  • Markwood-Tarrawingee Road
  • Pinkerton Crescent
  • Baker Street car park
  • Dowling Lane River Road
  • Oxley Flats Road
  • Stamps Lane / Dale Street / Ambrosio Road

properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Snowy River downstream of McKillops Bridge.

MINOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT MCKILLOPS BRIDGE, D/S BASIN CK AND ORBOST

Heavy rainfall associated with storm activity from Monday to Thursday in the eastern part of the upper Snowy catchment caused river level rises and minor to major flooding along the Snowy and Bombala rivers.

River levels have now peaked across all locations and levels are expected to continue falling overnight Friday and into Saturday.

No significant rainfall is expected during Friday and into Saturday.

The situation will continue to be monitored closely and warnings will be updated if required.

Snowy River downstream of McKillops Bridge:

Minor flooding is occurring along the Snowy River downstream of McKillops Bridge.

The Snowy River D/S Basin Ck is currently at 3.94 metres and falling, with minor flooding. The Snowy River D/S Basin Ck is expected to remain above the minor flood level (3.50 m) during Friday night and Saturday.

The Snowy River at Jarrahmond is below the minor flood level (4.10 m) and continuing to fall.

The river level is currently at 4.88 metres and falling, with minor flooding. The Snowy River at Orbost is likely to fall below the minor flood level (4.20 m) Saturday afternoon.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 

  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
Impacts in your area: 

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
  • Local roads may be closed and low bridges may be underwater.
  • Heavy rainfall may lead to an increased risk of landslides be aware of fallen earth, rocks, debris or trees.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

Snowy Catchments Campgrounds that are Closed due to Flooding: As of Wednesday 26th October, Long Point, Sandy Point and Wood Point campgrounds are close.

Farmers who have been impacted by flood and requires assistance or have urgent animal welfare needs, please contact AgVic - VicEmergency Hotline on 1800 226 226

The next update is expected by 29/10/2022 05:00 pm or as the situation changes.

properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Bunbartha, Kaarimba, and Mundoona.

  • FLOODWATER IS TOXIC - NEVER ENTER FLOODWATER  
  • Following severe water inundation, dangerous floodwaters remain within the Bunbartha, Kaarimba, and Mundoona area and you should avoid the flood affected area.
  • In particular the area north of Lords Road, Buchanan Road and up to Loch Garry Road are severely affected and under water.
  • Many septic tanks have failed and floodwaters are contaminated.
  • Floodwater is still over roads.
  • Never drive, walk or play in floodwater.
  • Only local traffic is allowed into the area.

Updated Community information: 
In flood-affected areas, there are now many cases of gastro (gastroenteritis, diarrhoea) causing people to get very sick.   

To prevent gastro always wash your hands after going to the toilet, before eating, preparing food, or cleaning your teeth etc. Only drink and wash, or wash clothes in known clean water.   

Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas. 
The wet ground conditions have resulted in many trees falling without warning.  If it gets windy, trees will become more unstable and deadly.  Never park, take shelter or camp under a tree.    

If you are planning to camp close to rivers or creeks DONT!    

Unexpected river rises are very likely after even small amounts of rainfall.

Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert. Never enter floodwater.   

In the VicEmergency App, add a watch zone for your campsite and regularly check emergency broadcasters via car radio if necessary.
What you should do:
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.

Impacts in your area:
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home and sheds may occur in some locations.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 31/10/2022 02:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Relief Centres: 
  • Shepparton Relief Centre is still open at the Shepparton Showgrounds, Macintosh Centre, Corner of Benalla Road and Thompson Street, Shepparton.
  • Nathalia Community Centre, 42 Robinson Street, Nathalia. 

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.
Health Messaging 
  • Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. 
  • Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home. Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas. 
  • Stay out of the water - skin contact with floodwater or mud can cause illness and skin infections. Cover cuts and if you are injured during your clean up; clean the wound and contact your doctor immediately.  
  • Private water supplies may also be contaminated from floodwater, debris and chemicals. If your water supply tastes, looks or smells unusual, do not use it for drinking, preparing food, and do not give it to animals.  
  • Medicines, stored at home and affected by flood water may now be unsafe and extreme caution should be taken in trying to salvage any medicines. 
  • Mosquitoes can also breed rapidly in stagnant waters. Drain any water from containers such as plant pots, tyres, buckets, and roof gutters to control mosquitos around your home. 
  • Flooding can also cause excessive mould growth which must be cleaned up before moving back to your home as it can make you sick. 
  • Any damaged gas or electricity supplies need to be declared safe by a qualified electrician or plumber. 
  • Do not use a portable generator indoors, they can produce carbon monoxide gas which could build up in a confined space and make you sick or be fatal. 
  • Food safety should also be considered and ALL food that has been flood damaged should be thrown away, including canned and packaged foods. 
  • It is important to look after your mental health and that of friends, family and neighbours. If at any time you are worried about your mental health or the mental health of a loved one, call Lifeline 13 11 14 or the Suicide Call Back Service on 1300 659 467.

Heavy rainfall associated with storm activity from Monday to Thursday in the eastern part of the upper Snowy catchment caused river level rises and minor to major flooding along the Snowy and Bombala rivers.

River levels have now peaked across all locations and levels are expected to continue falling overnight Friday and into Saturday.

No significant rainfall is expected during Friday and into Saturday.

The situation will continue to be monitored closely and warnings will be updated if required.

Snowy River to McKillops Bridge:

Minor flooding is occurring along the Snowy River to McKillops Bridge. Snowy Hydro advise Jindabyne is fulland spilling.

The Snowy River at McKillops Bridge is currently at 3.21 metres and falling, with minor flooding. The Snowy River at McKillops Bridge is expected to remain above the minor flood level (2.50 m) during Friday night and Saturday.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
Impacts in your area: 

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Heavy rainfall may lead to an increased risk of landslides be aware of fallen earth, rocks, debris or trees.
  • Boating in floodwaters is dangerous due to debris, submerged trees and other hidden dangers. 
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 29/10/2022 05:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline. 
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Goulburn River downstream of Shepparton

Updated Community information:

1. Illegal levees
In response to a number of concerns raised by community members, landowners are reminded that construction of works to divert the overland flow of water requires approval. To construct levees that interfere with overland water flows, without obtaining approval, is likely to impact on others and is also likely to be deemed illegal. 

We acknowledge these are difficult times for each impacted member of the community however, it is not appropriate to interfere with the natural overland flow of water as it can negatively impact on others. 


2. In flood-affected areas, there are now many cases of gastro (gastroenteritis, diarrhoea) causing people to get very sick.  
To prevent gastro always wash your hands after going to the toilet, before eating, preparing food, or cleaning your teeth etc. Only drink and wash, or wash clothes in known clean water.


MINOR FLOODING CURRENTLY OCCURRING AT DOWNSTREAM of LAKE EILDON, including at TAGGERTY, SEYMOUR, MURCHISON, SHEPPARTON AND MCCOYS BRIDGE 

MODERATE FLOODING EXPECTED AT DOWNSTREAM of LAKE EILDON SATURDAY MORNING  MODERATE FLOODING POSSIBLE AT SEYMOUR SUNDAY MORNING         
  • Moderate flooding is expected at Downstream of Lake Eildon during Saturday morning and may develop along the Goulburn River at Seymour during Sunday morning.   
  • Minor flooding is currently occurring along the Goulburn River catchment at Downstream  of Lake Eildon, Taggerty, Seymour, Murchison, Shepparton and McCoys Bridge.  
  • Goulburn Murray Water has advised that releases from Lake Eildon will be increasing from the current 24,000 ML/d up to around 30,000 ML/d by Saturday late morning.  
  • The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.  
  • The Goulburn River downstream of Lake Eildon is expected to exceed the moderate flood level (4.00 m) Saturday morning.  The river level is likely to reach around 4.40 metres late Saturday morning.  The Goulburn River at Seymour  is currently at 4.56 metres and steady, with minor flooding.  The Goulburn River at Seymour may reach the moderate flood level (5.20 m) Sunday morning.    
Goulburn River Seymour to Shepparton:  
  • Minor flooding is occurring along the Goulburn River Seymour to Shepparton. 
  • The Goulburn River at Murchison is currently around the minor flood level (9.00 m) and steady. The Goulburn River at Murchison is expected to remain around the minor flood level (9.00 m) during Saturday and into Sunday.  
The Goulburn River at Shepparton: 
  • is currently at 10.51 metres and falling, with minor flooding.  The Goulburn River at Shepparton is expected to remain above the minor flood level (9.50 m) during Saturday and into Sunday.  

Goulburn River downstream of Shepparton:  
  •  Please note The Murray Valley Highway is fully closed at Mc Coys Bridge due to Bridge damage. 
  • Minor flooding is occurring along the Goulburn River downstream of Shepparton.  
  • The Goulburn River at McCoys Bridge is currently at 9.93 metres and steady, below the moderate flood level (10.00 m).   
  • The Goulburn River at McCoys Bridge is expected to remain above the minor flood level (9.00 m) during Saturday and Sunday.



Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.

If you are planning to camp or go bush driving close to rivers or creeks this long weekend, DON'T!   

Unexpected river and creek levels are very likely even with small amounts of rain.   Support the local towns and make sure to set a watch zone for your location this long weekend and regularly check emergency radio broadcasters ( eg ABC radio) via your car radio if necessary.

Be aware of the increased likelihood of trees falling due to the very wet ground, especially in windy conditions. Never shelter under trees.    

Don't go fishing, kayaking, or boating. Floodwaters is dangerous due to debris, submerged trees and other hidden dangers. 
What you should do: 

  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater
  • In flood-affected areas, there are now many cases of gastro (gastroenteritis, diarrhoea) causing people to get very sick.   To prevent gastro always wash your hands after going to the toilet, before eating, preparing food, or cleaning your teeth etc. Only drink and wash, or wash clothes in known clean water.   Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted area
  •  Stagnant water can be harmful to your health. Dont swim, drink or wash in stagnant water. Smelly black water can be reported to EPA on 1800 560 760
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Review your emergency plan and check your emergency kit is fully stocked, if you have one. 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
When returning home:
  • Only turn your power on at the main electrical switchboard if water has not entered the property. 
  •  If water has entered your property, do not put the power back on until the property wiring has been tested by a licensed electrician.  
  •  If any appliances have been inundated, do not plug them in or switch them on until they have been tested by a licensed electrician.  
  •  For more information visit: https://esv.vic.gov.au/safety-education/emergencies/electrical-emergency/ Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
  •  Follow your emergency plan and locate your emergency kit, if you have one.
  • If cleaning after damage has occurred, protect your health and safety. 
  • Protect your lungs by wearing a N95 or P2 mask. 
  • Wear strong boots, gloves and protective clothing and wash your hands and clothes regularly.
  •  Stagnant water can be harmful to your health. Dont swim, drink or wash in stagnant water.
  •  Smelly black water can be reported to EPA on 1800 560 760
Generators

If you are using a generator, do not attempt to connect it to the wiring of your home. This is dangerous and illegal.

A generator should only be used outside, with an extension cord to supply power direct to appliances such as the fridge or freezer. Using a generator indoors creates a number of safety risks including the potential for carbon monoxide poisoning or a fire. 
Impacts in your area: 

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Many local roads may still be closed and low bridges may still be underwater.
  • The Murray Valley Highway is fully closed at Mc Coys Bridge due to Bridge damage.
  • For more information on road closures check the VicRoads website traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au.
  • Don't go fishing, kayaking, or boating. Floodwaters is dangerous due to debris, submerged trees and other hidden dangers. 
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 29/10/2022 06:30 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline. 
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.  
Recovery: 
 Flood Recovery Hotline is a single state-wide number, 1800 560 760, that Victorians impacted by the October 2022 floods can call for help or assistance with: Register for clean up on private property; Navigating financial and other support Access to temporary accommodation Mental health and wellbeing support The recovery hotline is open from 7:30am-7:30pm everyday.   Call 1800 560 760 or visit www.erv.vic.gov.au for further information. For life-threatening emergencies, call Triple Zero (000) immediately. For emergency assistance during floods call 132 500 for SES assistance.

Health Messaging 
  • Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home. 
  • Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas. 
  •  Stay out of the water - skin contact with floodwater or mud can cause illness and skin infections. Cover cuts and if you are injured during your clean up; clean the wound and contact your doctor immediately.  
  •  Private water supplies may also be contaminated from floodwater, debris and chemicals. If your water supply tastes, looks or smells unusual, do not use it for drinking, preparing food, and do not give it to animals.  Medicines, stored at home and affected by flood water may now be unsafe and extreme caution should be taken in trying to salvage any medicines. 
  •  Mosquitoes can also breed rapidly in stagnant waters. Drain any water from containers such as plant pots, tyres, buckets, and roof gutters to control mosquitos around your home. 
  •  Flooding can also cause excessive mould growth which must be cleaned up before moving back to your home as it can make you sick. 
  •  Any damaged gas or electricity supplies need to be declared safe by a qualified electrician or plumber. Do not use a portable generator indoors, they can produce carbon monoxide gas which could build up in a confined space and make you sick or be fatal. 
  •  Food safety should also be considered and ALL food that has been flood damaged should be thrown away   including canned and packaged foods. 
  •  It is important to look after your mental health and that of friends, family and neighbours. If at any time you are worried about your mental health or the mental health of a loved one, call Lifeline 13 11 14 or the Suicide Call Back Service on 1300 659 467.

Register Find Unite - Red Cross 
Red Cross has opened Register.Find.Reunite. and is urging people affected by the Victorian Floods to get in touch with their families and friends. Register.Find.Reunite. helps find and reunite family, friends and loved ones during a disaster. People can register on the Red Cross website at register.redcross.org.au, or by phone at 1800 727 077. This is a community message to advise the community not to build own levees as it changes the flow of the water and impacting other properties.
